var __index = {"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"],"fields":{"title":{"boost":1000.0},"text":{"boost":1.0},"tags":{"boost":1000000.0}}},"docs":[{"location":"index.html","title":"CellCounter","text":"<p>Automated cFos cell counting and brain region mapping for whole-brain microscopy images.</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    A[TIFF Images] --&gt; B[Registration]\n    A --&gt; C[Cell Detection]\n    C --&gt; D[Region Mapping]\n    B --&gt; D\n    D --&gt; E[Results]\n\n    style A fill:#e1f5fe\n    style E fill:#c8e6c9</code></pre>"},{"location":"index.html#what-it-does","title":"What it does","text":"<ol> <li>Register your microscopy images to a reference atlas (e.g., Allen Mouse Brain Atlas)</li> <li>Detect cFos-positive cells using watershed segmentation</li> <li>Map detected cells to anatomical brain regions</li> </ol>"},{"location":"index.html#quick-start","title":"Quick Start","text":"<pre><code># Install\nuv sync\n\n# Initialize atlas data\nuv run cellcounter-init\n\n# Create a new project\nuv run cellcounter-make-project\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"index.html#features","title":"Features","text":"<ul> <li>GPU Acceleration - CUDA support via CuPy for large images (~90GB)</li> <li>Memory Efficient - Dask-powered chunked processing</li> <li>Configurable - All parameters via Pydantic models</li> <li>Visual QC - Built-in visual check tools with napari</li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#next-steps","title":"Next Steps","text":"<ul> <li> Getting Started</li> </ul> <p>Install and run your first analysis</p> <p> Installation</p> <ul> <li> Tutorials</li> </ul> <p>Learn the workflow step by step</p> <p> Quick Start</p> <ul> <li> How-To Guides</li> </ul> <p>Solve specific problems</p> <p> Batch Processing</p> <ul> <li> API Reference</li> </ul> <p>Browse the code documentation</p> <p> Pipeline API</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html","title":"Architecture","text":"<p>Understanding how CellCounter is organized and how the pieces fit together.</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#why-this-architecture","title":"Why This Architecture?","text":"<p>CellCounter is designed for whole-brain microscopy images that are: - Very large: ~90GB per brain - High resolution: often 1-2 \u00b5m per voxel - Compute-intensive: registration, filtering, segmentation</p> <p>The architecture addresses these challenges through: 1. Chunked storage (Zarr) \u2014 memory-efficient access 2. Lazy evaluation (Dask) \u2014 compute only what's needed 3. GPU acceleration (CuPy) \u2014 fast array operations 4. Modular design \u2014 easy to extend and maintain</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#directory-structure","title":"Directory Structure","text":"<pre><code>src/cellcounter/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 pipeline/               # Main workflow orchestration\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 abstract_pipeline.py   # Base class with GPU/CPU switching\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 pipeline.py            # Full pipeline implementation\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 visual_check.py        # QC visualization tools\n\u2502\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 models/                 # Data models (Pydantic)\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 proj_config.py         # Configuration tree root\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 proj_config/           # Config sub-models\n\u2502   \u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 cell_counting_config.py\n\u2502   \u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 registration_config.py\n\u2502   \u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 ...\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 fp_models/             # Filepath models\n\u2502       \u251c\u2500\u2500 proj_fp.py\n\u2502       \u251c\u2500\u2500 ref_fp.py\n\u2502       \u2514\u2500\u2500 ...\n\u2502\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 funcs/                  # Core algorithms\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 cpu_cellc_funcs.py     # CPU cell counting functions\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 gpu_cellc_funcs.py     # GPU-accelerated wrappers\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 elastix_funcs.py       # Image registration\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 map_funcs.py           # Region mapping\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 io_funcs.py            # File I/O\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 ...\n\u2502\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 constants/              # Enums and constants\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 annotations.py\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 coords.py\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 ...\n\u2502\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 utils/                  # Utilities\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 dask_utils.py          # Dask cluster helpers\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 viewer.py              # Napari viewer\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 union_find.py          # Cross-chunk label merging\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 ...\n\u2502\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 scripts/                # CLI entry points\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 init.py                # Download atlas\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 make_project.py        # Create new project\n\u2502\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 templates/              # User templates\n    \u251c\u2500\u2500 run_pipeline.py\n    \u2514\u2500\u2500 view_img.py\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#design-patterns","title":"Design Patterns","text":""},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#1-gpucpu-backend-switching","title":"1. GPU/CPU Backend Switching","text":"<p>Problem: Need to support both GPU (fast) and CPU (portable) execution.</p> <p>Solution: Injectable backend with runtime switching.</p> <pre><code># Base class uses numpy by default\nclass CpuCellcFuncs:\n    def __init__(self, xp=np, xdimage=scipy.ndimage):\n        self.xp = xp  # numpy or cupy\n        # All methods use self.xp instead of np directly\n\n# GPU wrapper inherits and converts\nclass GpuCellcFuncs(CpuCellcFuncs):\n    _GPU_METHODS = [\"tophat_filt\", \"dog_filt\", ...]\n    # Returns cupy arrays \u2192 auto-converts to numpy\n</code></pre> <p>Usage:</p> <pre><code>pipeline = Pipeline(\"/path/to/project\")\n\n# Switch at runtime\npipeline.set_gpu(enabled=True)   # Use CuPy\npipeline.set_gpu(enabled=False)  # Use NumPy\n</code></pre> <p>This enables: - Same code runs on both GPU and CPU - Easy fallback when GPU unavailable - Easy testing and debugging on CPU</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#2-file-protection-with-overwrite-guard","title":"2. File Protection with Overwrite Guard","text":"<p>Problem: Expensive computations shouldn't be accidentally overwritten.</p> <p>Solution: Decorator that checks for existing files.</p> <pre><code>def _check_overwrite(*fp_attrs: str):\n    \"\"\"Decorator to skip if outputs exist.\"\"\"\n    def decorator(func):\n        def wrapper(self, *args, overwrite: bool = False, **kwargs):\n            if not overwrite:\n                for attr in fp_attrs:\n                    fp = getattr(self.pfm, attr)\n                    if fp.exists():\n                        logger.warning(\n                            \"Output exists, skipping. \"\n                            \"Use overwrite=True to recompute.\"\n                        )\n                        return None\n            return func(self, *args, **overwrite, **kwargs)\n        return wrapper\n    return decorator\n\nclass Pipeline:\n    @_check_overwrite(\"downsmpl1\")\n    def reg_img_rough(self, *, overwrite: bool = False):\n        # Won't recompute unless overwrite=True\n        ...\n</code></pre> <p>Benefits: - Safe to re-run scripts - Explicit control over recomputation - Prevents accidental data loss</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#3-dask-cluster-context-managers","title":"3. Dask Cluster Context Managers","text":"<p>Problem: Different operations need different compute resources.</p> <p>Solution: Cluster factory methods with context managers.</p> <pre><code>class AbstractPipeline:\n    def gpu_cluster(self):\n        \"\"\"Single GPU worker for GPU ops.\"\"\"\n        return LocalCUDACluster(n_workers=1)\n\n    def heavy_cluster(self):\n        \"\"\"Few workers, high memory for watershed.\"\"\"\n        return LocalCluster(\n            n_workers=1,\n            threads_per_worker=6\n        )\n\n    def busy_cluster(self):\n        \"\"\"Many workers for I/O.\"\"\"\n        return LocalCluster(\n            n_workers=4,\n            threads_per_worker=1\n        )\n</code></pre> <p>Usage:</p> <pre><code>from cellcounter.utils.dask_utils import cluster_process\n\nwith cluster_process(self.gpu_cluster()):\n    result = da.map_blocks(self.cellc_funcs.tophat_filt, arr)\n    disk_cache(result, output_path)\n# Cluster automatically cleaned up\n</code></pre> <p>Benefits: - Appropriate resources for each operation - Automatic cleanup - No resource conflicts</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#4-configuration-as-code","title":"4. Configuration as Code","text":"<p>Problem: Many parameters need to be saved, versioned, and shared.</p> <p>Solution: Pydantic models with JSON serialization.</p> <pre><code>class ProjConfig(BaseModel):\n    chunks: DimsConfig\n    cell_counting: CellCountingConfig\n    registration: RegistrationConfig\n    ...\n\n    def write_file(self, fp: Path) -&gt; None:\n        with fp.open(\"w\") as f:\n            f.write(self.model_dump_json(indent=2))\n\n    @classmethod\n    def read_file(cls, fp: Path) -&gt; Self:\n        return cls.model_validate(json.load(f.open()))\n</code></pre> <p>Benefits: - Type-safe configuration - Auto-validation on load - Human-readable JSON format - Easy to version control</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#5-filepath-models","title":"5. Filepath Models","text":"<p>Problem: Many files to track across project structure.</p> <p>Solution: Dataclass models for file paths.</p> <pre><code>@dataclass\nclass ProjFp:\n    root_dir: Path\n\n    @property\n    def config_fp(self) -&gt; Path:\n        return self.root_dir / \"config.json\"\n\n    @property\n    def raw(self) -&gt; Path:\n        return self.cellcount_dir / \"raw.zarr\"\n\n    @property\n    def cells_agg_csv(self) -&gt; Path:\n        return self.cellcount_dir / \"cells_agg.csv\"\n</code></pre> <p>Benefits: - Centralized path management - Consistent naming - Auto-created directories - Type hints for autocomplete</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#data-flow","title":"Data Flow","text":"<p>The pipeline processes data in three stages:</p> <pre><code>flowchart TB\n    subgraph Input[\"\ud83d\udcc1 Input\"]\n        TIFF[Multi-page TIFF]\n    end\n\n    subgraph Reg[\"\ud83d\udd27 Registration\"]\n        ZARR[Zarr Array&lt;br/&gt;chunked storage]\n        DOWN1[Rough Downsample&lt;br/&gt;integer stride]\n        DOWN2[Fine Downsample&lt;br/&gt;Gaussian zoom]\n        TRIM[Trim to ROI]\n        BOUND[Intensity Clip]\n        REG[Registered&lt;br/&gt;atlas space]\n    end\n\n    subgraph CellC[\"\ud83d\udd2c Cell Counting\"]\n        TOPHAT[Background Removal&lt;br/&gt;top-hat filter]\n        DOG[Edge Enhancement&lt;br/&gt;Difference of Gaussians]\n        ADAPT[Adaptive Thresholding]\n        THRESH[Binary Threshold]\n        LABEL[Label Contiguous]\n        FILTER1[Size Filter #1]\n        MAXIMA[Detect Local Maxima]\n        WSHED[Watershed Segmentation]\n        FILTER2[Size Filter #2]\n        CELLS[Cell Table&lt;br/&gt;coordinates + measurements]\n    end\n\n    subgraph Map[\"\ud83d\uddfa\ufe0f Region Mapping\"]\n        TRFM[Transform Coordinates&lt;br/&gt;to atlas space]\n        MAPPED[Assign Region IDs]\n        AGG[Aggregate by Region]\n        CSV[CSV Export]\n    end\n\n    TIFF --&gt; ZARR\n    ZARR --&gt; DOWN1 --&gt; DOWN2 --&gt; TRIM --&gt; BOUND --&gt; REG\n    ZARR --&gt; TOPHAT --&gt; DOG --&gt; ADAPT --&gt; THRESH --&gt; LABEL --&gt; FILTER1 --&gt; MAXIMA --&gt; WSHED --&gt; FILTER2 --&gt; CELLS\n    REG --&gt; TRFM\n    CELLS --&gt; TRFM --&gt; MAPPED --&gt; AGG --&gt; CSV</code></pre>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#memory-management","title":"Memory Management","text":"<p>Whole-brain images (~90GB) can't fit in RAM. Solutions:</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#1-zarr-chunked-storage","title":"1. Zarr Chunked Storage","text":"<pre><code>raw.zarr/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 .zarray          # Array metadata\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 0.0.0            # Chunk (z=0-500, y=0-500, x=0-500)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 0.0.1            # Chunk (z=0-500, y=0-500, x=500-1000)\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 ...              # ~150 chunks for whole brain\n</code></pre> <ul> <li>Only load chunks being processed</li> <li>Parallel read/write</li> <li>Efficient for both SSD and network storage</li> </ul>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#2-dask-lazy-evaluation","title":"2. Dask Lazy Evaluation","text":"<pre><code># Doesn't load data yet \u2014 just builds task graph\nraw_arr = da.from_zarr(\"raw.zarr\")\nfiltered = da.map_blocks(tophat_filt, raw_arr)\n\n# Only compute when needed\ndisk_cache(filtered, \"output.zarr\")  # Materializes\n</code></pre> <p>Benefits: - No intermediate arrays in memory - Task optimization before execution - Automatic parallelism</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#3-gpu-single-worker","title":"3. GPU Single-Worker","text":"<pre><code>with cluster_process(self.gpu_cluster()):\n    # n_workers=1 prevents GPU OOM\n    result = da.map_blocks(gpu_operation, arr)\n</code></pre> <p>GPU memory is limited \u2014 single worker ensures: - Only one chunk on GPU at a time - No contention for VRAM - Predictable memory usage</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#4-union-find-for-cross-chunk-merging","title":"4. Union-Find for Cross-Chunk Merging","text":"<p>When labeling connected components across chunks:</p> <pre><code>def _spatial_connect_count(self, label_arr):\n    # 1. Find connections at chunk boundaries\n    pairs = find_boundary_pairs(label_arr)\n\n    # 2. Union-Find merges labels\n    uf = UnionFind()\n    for a, b in pairs:\n        uf.union(a, b)\n\n    # 3. Map to unified labels\n    return uf.remap(label_arr)\n</code></pre> <p>This ensures cells spanning multiple chunks are counted once.</p>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#extending-cellcounter","title":"Extending CellCounter","text":""},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#add-a-new-pipeline-step","title":"Add a New Pipeline Step","text":"<pre><code>class Pipeline:\n    @_check_overwrite(\"new_output\")\n    def my_new_step(self, *, overwrite: bool = False):\n        \"\"\"Custom processing step.\"\"\"\n        with cluster_process(self.gpu_cluster()):\n            raw = da.from_zarr(self.pfm.raw)\n            result = da.map_blocks(my_custom_func, raw)\n            disk_cache(result, self.pfm.my_new_output)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#add-a-new-cell-counting-function","title":"Add a New Cell Counting Function","text":"<pre><code>class CpuCellcFuncs:\n    def my_filter(self, arr: np.ndarray) -&gt; np.ndarray:\n        \"\"\"Custom filter implementation.\"\"\"\n        return self.xp.some_operation(arr)\n\nclass GpuCellcFuncs(CpuCellcFuncs):\n    _GPU_METHODS = [..., \"my_filter\"]  # Auto-GPU support\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#custom-configuration","title":"Custom Configuration","text":"<pre><code>class MyConfig(BaseModel):\n    my_param: float = 1.0\n\nclass ProjConfig(BaseModel):\n    ...\n    my_config: MyConfig = MyConfig()\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#testing-architecture","title":"Testing Architecture","text":"<p>The modular design enables testing at multiple levels:</p> Level What to Test Example Unit Individual functions <code>test_tophat_filter()</code> Integration Pipeline steps <code>test_registration_flow()</code> End-to-end Full pipeline <code>test_small_image()</code>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#mock-gpu-for-testing","title":"Mock GPU for Testing","text":"<pre><code>def test_cell_counting_cpu():\n    pipeline = Pipeline(\"/tmp/test\", tuning=True)\n    pipeline.set_gpu(enabled=False)  # Force CPU\n    pipeline.tophat_filter()\n    # ... asserts\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"explanation/architecture.html#performance-considerations","title":"Performance Considerations","text":"Operation Bottleneck Optimization TIFF\u2192Zarr Disk I/O SSD, parallel writing Registration Elastix Multi-thread elastix Top-hat GPU memory Right-sized chunks Watershed Memory Single worker, CPU CSV export Aggregation Parquet intermediate <p>The architecture separates these concerns so each can be optimized independently.</p>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html","title":"Cell Detection Algorithm","text":"<p>How CellCounter identifies and counts cFos-positive cells.</p>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#overview","title":"Overview","text":"<p>cFos is a nuclear protein that marks recently active neurons. Cell detection involves:</p> <ol> <li>Enhancing cell-like structures \u2014 Filtering to highlight nuclei</li> <li>Separating foreground from background \u2014 Thresholding</li> <li>Finding individual cell centers \u2014 Local maxima detection</li> <li>Separating touching cells \u2014 Watershed segmentation</li> <li>Filtering by size \u2014 Removing debris and artifacts</li> </ol> <p>The pipeline is designed for images where: - Cells appear as bright, roughly spherical spots - Background varies across the image - Cells may touch or overlap</p>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#the-pipeline-step-by-step","title":"The Pipeline Step by Step","text":""},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#step-1-background-removal-top-hat-filter","title":"Step 1: Background Removal (Top-Hat Filter)","text":"<p>Goal: Remove large-scale illumination variations and uneven background.</p> <p>How it works: - Morphological opening with a large sphere removes bright objects - Subtracting this from original leaves only small bright objects</p> <pre><code># Conceptually:\nbackground = morphological_opening(image, radius=10)\ncells = image - background\n</code></pre> <p>Visual effect:</p> Before After Uneven illumination across field Uniform background, bright cells stand out Dark corners, bright center Consistent baseline <p>Parameters: - <code>tophat_radius</code>: Radius of structuring element (voxels)   - Default: 10   - Smaller (5-8): For small cells or uneven background   - Larger (12-20): For large cells or smooth background</p>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#step-2-edge-enhancement-difference-of-gaussians","title":"Step 2: Edge Enhancement (Difference of Gaussians)","text":"<p>Goal: Highlight cell boundaries and suppress noise.</p> <p>How it works: - Gaussian blur at small sigma (preserves cells) - Gaussian blur at large sigma (preserves background) - Subtract: edges remain, uniform regions cancel</p> <pre><code># Conceptually:\nsmall_blur = gaussian_filter(image, sigma=1)\nlarge_blur = gaussian_filter(image, sigma=4)\nedges = small_blur - large_blur\n</code></pre> <p>Why it helps: - Cells have strong edges \u2192 enhanced - Background varies slowly \u2192 suppressed - Small noise \u2192 smoothed out</p> <p>Visual effect:</p> Before After Whole cells bright, fuzzy boundaries Edges emphasized, interiors uniform Some noise visible Noise reduced <p>Parameters: - <code>dog_sigma1</code>: Small Gaussian sigma (voxels)   - Default: 1   - Match to cell radius - <code>dog_sigma2</code>: Large Gaussian sigma (voxels)   - Default: 4   - Typically 3-4 \u00d7 sigma1</p>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#step-3-adaptive-threshold-preparation","title":"Step 3: Adaptive Threshold Preparation","text":"<p>Goal: Handle varying background intensity across the image.</p> <p>How it works: - Large Gaussian smooths over cells - Subtracts this slowly-varying background - Result: normalized image suitable for global threshold</p> <pre><code># Conceptually:\nbackground = gaussian_filter(image, sigma=101)\nnormalized = image - background\n</code></pre> <p>Why it's needed: Some brain regions are brighter than others due to: - Staining variation - Tissue thickness differences - Light sheet illumination falloff</p>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#step-4-manual-thresholding","title":"Step 4: Manual Thresholding","text":"<p>Goal: Create binary mask (cell / not-cell).</p> <p>How it works: - Pixels above threshold \u2192 foreground (1) - Pixels below threshold \u2192 background (0)</p> <pre><code>binary_image = filtered_image &gt; threshold_value\n</code></pre> <p>Visual effect:</p> Before After Grayscale, cells brighter Black and white mask Some dim cells May be lost if threshold too high Some bright debris May be kept if threshold too low <p>Parameters: - <code>threshd_value</code>: Intensity threshold   - Default: 60   - Lower (40): More sensitive, more false positives   - Higher (80): More stringent, fewer false positives</p> <p>Finding the Right Threshold</p> <p>Start with default (60), visualize with <code>combine_cellc()</code>, and adjust up/down by 10-20 until reaching good balance.</p>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#step-5-6-label-and-compute-volumes","title":"Step 5-6: Label and Compute Volumes","text":"<p>Goal: Identify connected regions and measure their sizes.</p> <p>How it works: 1. Connected component labeling: each contiguous foreground region gets unique ID 2. Union-Find algorithm merges labels across chunk boundaries 3. Volume computed for each component</p> <p>Challenge: Cross-chunk connections</p> <pre><code>\u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510\n\u2502   1   \u2502   1   \u2502  \u2190 Same cell spans both chunks!\n\u2502   1   \u2502   1   \u2502\n\u251c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2524\n\u2502   2   \u2502   3   \u2502\n\u2502   2   \u2502   3   \u2502\n\u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2534\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2518\n    \u2193 Union-Find\n\u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510\n\u2502   A   \u2502   A   \u2502  \u2190 Both labeled 'A'\n\u2502   A   \u2502   A   \u2502\n\u251c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2524\n\u2502   B   \u2502   C   \u2502\n\u2502   B   \u2502   C   \u2502\n\u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2534\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2518\n</code></pre> <p>The custom <code>UnionFind</code> class efficiently merges these labels.</p>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#step-7-size-filtering-1","title":"Step 7: Size Filtering #1","text":"<p>Goal: Remove obviously wrong objects (too small = noise, too large = artifacts).</p> <pre><code>keep = (volume &gt; min_threshd_size) &amp; (volume &lt; max_threshd_size)\n</code></pre> <p>What it removes: - <code>min_threshd_size</code> (default: 100): Dust, noise pixels - <code>max_threshd_size</code> (default: 9000): Clusters, artifacts</p> <p>Note: This is a coarse filter. Fine-tuning happens after watershed.</p>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#step-8-local-maxima-detection","title":"Step 8: Local Maxima Detection","text":"<p>Goal: Find the center point of each cell.</p> <p>How it works: - For each pixel, check if it's the maximum in local neighborhood - Only keep maxima within valid regions (post-filter mask)</p> <pre><code>for each pixel:\n    neighborhood = image[pixel-radius:pixel+radius]\n    if image[pixel] == max(neighborhood):\n        mark as maxima\n</code></pre> <p>Visual effect:</p> Before After Filtered threshold mask Single-pixel markers at cell centers Connected regions One marker per cell <p>Parameters: - <code>maxima_radius</code>: Neighborhood size (voxels)   - Default: 10   - Smaller: More sensitive, may split cells   - Larger: Less sensitive, may merge nearby cells</p> <p>Challenge: Touching cells share a connected region but should have separate maxima.</p>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#step-9-10-label-maxima-and-watershed-segmentation","title":"Step 9-10: Label Maxima and Watershed Segmentation","text":"<p>Goal: Separate touching cells.</p> <p>How watershed works: 1. Treat inverted image as a terrain (dark = low, bright = high) 2. Maxima are \"basins\" that will collect \"water\" 3. Flood from each maxima simultaneously 4. Where floods meet \u2192 boundaries drawn</p> <pre><code>Image Intensity (inverted):\n   \u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\n   \u2588\u2588a\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588b\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588   \u2190 Two maxima (a, b) in valley\n   \u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\n      \u2191     \u2191\n   Basins that will flood upward\n\nWatershed Result:\n   AAAAAAA|BBBBBBB\n   AAAAAAA|BBBBBBB  \u2190 Boundary at midpoint\n   AAAAAAA|BBBBBBB\n</code></pre> <p>Why it works for cells: - Cells are brighter in center \u2192 form basins - Touching cells have saddle point between \u2192 watershed boundary - Separates overlapping nuclei</p> <p>Visual effect:</p> Before Watershed After Watershed Single merged region for touching cells Each cell has unique label Cannot count individual cells Cell count = number of labels"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#step-11-12-compute-watershed-volumes-and-filter","title":"Step 11-12: Compute Watershed Volumes and Filter","text":"<p>Goal: Final size filtering on actual cells.</p> <p>Same as steps 5-7, but applied to watershed segments:</p> <pre><code># Filter watershed cells\nkeep = (volume &gt; min_wshed_size) &amp; (volume &lt; max_wshed_size)\n</code></pre> <p>Parameters: - <code>min_wshed_size</code>: Minimum final cell size (default: 1) - <code>max_wshed_size</code>: Maximum final cell size (default: 700)</p> <p>These are the most important parameters for tuning: - Too low: Dust included - Too high: Real cells excluded - Typical cFos nucleus: 50-300 voxels (at 1\u00b5m resolution)</p>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#step-13-save-cells-table","title":"Step 13: Save Cells Table","text":"<p>Goal: Extract measurements for each detected cell.</p> <p>For each valid cell: - Center coordinates (z, y, x) - Volume (voxels) - Sum intensity (total fluorescence) - Mean intensity (average brightness)</p> <p>Output: Parquet file with columns:</p> z y x label volume sum_intensity mean_intensity 100 1500 2000 1 127 5432 42.8 102 1505 2010 2 98 4100 41.8 ... ... ... ... ... ... ..."},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#algorithm-parameters-summary","title":"Algorithm Parameters Summary","text":"Parameter Step Default Effect of Increase Effect of Decrease <code>tophat_radius</code> Background removal 10 More background removed Less background removed <code>dog_sigma1</code> Edge detection 1 Larger features Smaller features <code>dog_sigma2</code> Edge detection 4 Smoother edges Sharper edges <code>large_gauss_radius</code> Adaptive thresh 101 More normalization Less normalization <code>threshd_value</code> Thresholding 60 Fewer cells detected More cells detected <code>min_threshd_size</code> Pre-filter 100 Fewer objects More objects <code>max_threshd_size</code> Pre-filter 9000 Allows larger Rejects larger <code>maxima_radius</code> Maxima detection 10 Fewer maxima More maxima <code>min_wshed_size</code> Final filter 1 Rejects small Keeps small <code>max_wshed_size</code> Final filter 700 Rejects large Keeps large"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#visual-summary","title":"Visual Summary","text":"<pre><code>flowchart LR\n    subgraph Raw[\"1. Raw Image\"]\n        R[\"\ud83d\udcf7&lt;br/&gt;Brightness = cFos level\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph Filter[\"2. Filtering\"]\n        TOPHAT[\"Top-hat&lt;br/&gt;remove bg\"]\n        DOG[\"DoG&lt;br/&gt;enhance edges\"]\n        ADAPT[\"Gauss sub&lt;br/&gt;normalize\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph Detect[\"3. Detection\"]\n        THRESH[\"Threshold&lt;br/&gt;binary mask\"]\n        MAXIMA[\"Local maxima&lt;br/&gt;find centers\"]\n        WSHED[\"Watershed&lt;br/&gt;separate cells\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph Filter2[\"4. Filtering\"]\n        VOL[\"Size filter&lt;br/&gt;remove debris\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph Output[\"5. Output\"]\n        CELLS[\"\ud83d\udcca Cell table&lt;br/&gt;coordinates + metrics\"]\n    end\n\n    R --&gt; TOPHAT --&gt; DOG --&gt; ADAPT --&gt; THRESH --&gt; MAXIMA --&gt; WSHED --&gt; VOL --&gt; CELLS</code></pre>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#advantages-of-this-approach","title":"Advantages of This Approach","text":"<ol> <li>No training data needed \u2014 Traditional image processing, not deep learning</li> <li>Interpretable parameters \u2014 Each knob has clear meaning</li> <li>Fast on GPU \u2014 All operations parallelize well</li> <li>Memory efficient \u2014 Dask handles chunked processing</li> <li>Scales to large images \u2014 Tested on ~90GB whole brains</li> </ol>"},{"location":"explanation/cell-detection.html#limitations","title":"Limitations","text":"<ol> <li>Assumes spherical cells \u2014 Elongated cells may be split</li> <li>Requires staining quality \u2014 Poor SNR defeats even best parameters</li> <li>Parameter tuning needed \u2014 Not fully automatic</li> <li>No cell classification \u2014 Can't distinguish cell types by morphology</li> </ol> <p>For datasets where these limitations matter, deep learning approaches (StarDist, Cellpose) may be more appropriate, though they have their own trade-offs (training data, compute cost, GPU memory).</p>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html","title":"Batch Processing","text":"<p>Process multiple images efficiently using a single script.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#when-to-use-batch-processing","title":"When to Use Batch Processing","text":"<p>Use batch processing when you have:</p> <ul> <li>Multiple animals from the same experiment</li> <li>Consistent imaging parameters across samples</li> <li>Need for reproducible, automated analysis</li> </ul> <p>Advantages of Batch Processing</p> <ul> <li>Consistent parameters across all samples</li> <li>Overnight/background processing</li> <li>Easy to rerun with different parameters</li> <li>Automatic result aggregation</li> </ul>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#data-organization","title":"Data Organization","text":"<p>Organize your data consistently:</p> <pre><code>stitched_imgs/                    # Raw images\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 mouse_01/\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 tile_001.tiff\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 tile_002.tiff\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 ...\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 mouse_02/\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 ...\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 mouse_03/\n    \u2514\u2500\u2500 ...\n\nanalysis_outputs/                 # Results (auto-created)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 mouse_01/\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 config.json\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 cellcount/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 mouse_02/\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 mouse_03/\n</code></pre> <p>Naming Matters</p> <p>Use descriptive, consistent folder names. These become your sample identifiers in the final aggregated results.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#creating-a-batch-script","title":"Creating a Batch Script","text":"<p>CellCounter provides a template you can customize. When you run <code>cellcounter-make-project</code>, a <code>run_pipeline.py</code> file is created.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#step-1-generate-template","title":"Step 1: Generate Template","text":"<pre><code>cd /path/to/your/analysis\nuv run cellcounter-make-project\n# Choose any name; we'll edit the generated script\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#step-2-edit-the-script","title":"Step 2: Edit the Script","text":"<p>Open <code>run_pipeline.py</code> and customize:</p> <pre><code>from pathlib import Path\nfrom cellcounter import Pipeline, VisualCheck\nfrom cellcounter.funcs.batch_combine_funcs import combine_root\n\n# =========================================\n# CHANGE THESE PATHS\nstitched_imgs_dir = Path(\"/path/to/stitched_imgs\")\nanalysis_root_dir = Path(\"/path/to/analysis_outputs\")\noverwrite = False  # Set to True to reprocess existing files\n# =========================================\n\n# Get list of folders to process\nimgs_ls = Pipeline.get_imgs_ls(stitched_imgs_dir)\n# Or specify manually:\n# imgs_ls = [\"mouse_01\", \"mouse_02\"]\n\nprint(f\"Found {len(imgs_ls)} images to process\")\nfor img_name in imgs_ls:\n    print(f\"\\nProcessing: {img_name}\")\n\n    in_fp = stitched_imgs_dir / img_name\n    analysis_img_dir = analysis_root_dir / img_name\n\n    try:\n        # Create pipeline\n        pipeline = Pipeline(analysis_img_dir)\n\n        # =========================================================\n        # CONFIGURE PARAMETERS HERE (applied to all images)\n        # =========================================================\n        pipeline.update_config(\n            # Chunks\n            chunks={\"z\": 500, \"y\": 500, \"x\": 500},\n\n            # Registration\n            registration={\n                \"ref_orientation\": {\"z\": -2, \"y\": 3, \"x\": 1},\n                \"downsample_rough\": {\"z\": 3, \"y\": 6, \"x\": 6},\n            },\n\n            # Cell counting (tune these first!)\n            cell_counting={\n                \"tophat_radius\": 10,\n                \"threshd_value\": 60,\n                \"min_wshed_size\": 1,\n                \"max_wshed_size\": 700,\n            },\n\n            # Tuning crop for parameter validation\n            tuning_trim={\n                \"z\": {\"start\": 700, \"stop\": 800, \"step\": None},\n                \"y\": {\"start\": 1000, \"stop\": 3000, \"step\": None},\n                \"x\": {\"start\": 1000, \"stop\": 3000, \"step\": None},\n            },\n        )\n\n        # Run full pipeline\n        pipeline.run_pipeline(str(in_fp), overwrite=overwrite)\n\n        # Run visual checks\n        vc = VisualCheck(analysis_img_dir, tuning=False)\n        vc.combine_reg(overwrite=overwrite)\n\n        print(f\"\u2713 Completed: {img_name}\")\n\n    except Exception as e:\n        print(f\"\u2717 Error in {img_name}: {e}\")\n        # Continue with next image\n\n# Combine all results into single CSV\nprint(\"\\nCombining results...\")\ncombine_root(analysis_root_dir, analysis_root_dir.parent, overwrite=True)\nprint(\"\u2713 Batch processing complete!\")\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#step-3-run-the-script","title":"Step 3: Run the Script","text":"<pre><code>cd /path/to/your/analysis\nuv run python run_pipeline.py\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#recommended-workflow","title":"Recommended Workflow","text":"<p>For best results with multiple images:</p>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#phase-1-tune-on-representative-sample","title":"Phase 1: Tune on Representative Sample","text":"<ol> <li>Pick one representative image</li> <li>Run tuning workflow to find good parameters</li> <li>Verify results with visual checks</li> <li>Note the working parameters</li> </ol>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#phase-2-test-on-2-3-images","title":"Phase 2: Test on 2-3 Images","text":"<pre><code># Process just a few first\nimgs_ls = [\"mouse_01\", \"mouse_02\"]\n\nfor img_name in imgs_ls:\n    # ... processing code\n</code></pre> <p>Check that: - Registration looks good for all - Cell detection works consistently - No unexpected errors</p>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#phase-3-process-all-images","title":"Phase 3: Process All Images","text":"<pre><code># Process all images\nimgs_ls = Pipeline.get_imgs_ls(stitched_imgs_dir)\n# Or: imgs_ls = [\"mouse_01\", \"mouse_02\", \"mouse_03\", ... all]\n</code></pre> <p>Run overnight or in background:</p> <pre><code># Run with nohup to survive logout\nnohup uv run python run_pipeline.py &gt; batch.log 2&gt;&amp;1 &amp;\n\n# Check progress\ntail -f batch.log\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#step-by-step-control","title":"Step-by-Step Control","text":"<p>For more control over the pipeline, run steps individually:</p> <pre><code>for img_name in imgs_ls:\n    in_fp = stitched_imgs_dir / img_name\n    analysis_img_dir = analysis_root_dir / img_name\n    pipeline = Pipeline(analysis_img_dir)\n\n    # Registration (run once per image)\n    if not (analysis_img_dir / \"cellcount\" / \"regresult.tiff\").exists():\n        pipeline.tiff2zarr(in_fp)\n        pipeline.reg_ref_prepare()\n        pipeline.reg_img_rough()\n        pipeline.reg_img_fine()\n        pipeline.reg_img_trim()\n        pipeline.reg_img_bound()\n        pipeline.reg_elastix()\n        pipeline.make_tuning_arr()\n    else:\n        print(f\"Registration already done for {img_name}\")\n\n    # Cell counting (tune=false for full run)\n    pipeline = Pipeline(analysis_img_dir, tuning=False)\n    pipeline.tophat_filter()\n    pipeline.dog_filter()\n    pipeline.adaptive_threshold_prep()\n    pipeline.threshold()\n    # ... (all cell counting steps)\n    pipeline.cells2csv()\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#handling-failures","title":"Handling Failures","text":"<p>Some images may fail. Handle gracefully:</p> <pre><code>import traceback\n\nfailed = []\nsuccessful = []\n\nfor img_name in imgs_ls:\n    try:\n        # ... processing code ...\n        successful.append(img_name)\n    except Exception as e:\n        print(f\"\u2717 Failed: {img_name}\")\n        print(traceback.format_exc())\n        failed.append((img_name, str(e)))\n\n# Summary\nprint(f\"\\n=== SUMMARY ===\")\nprint(f\"Successful: {len(successful)}\")\nprint(f\"Failed: {len(failed)}\")\nfor name, error in failed:\n    print(f\"  - {name}: {error}\")\n\n# Retry failed images (after fixing issues)\n# imgs_ls = [name for name, _ in failed]\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#combining-results","title":"Combining Results","text":"<p>After all images are processed, aggregate results:</p> <pre><code>from cellcounter.funcs.batch_combine_funcs import combine_root\n\n# Combine all cells_agg.csv files\ncombine_root(\n    src_root=analysis_root_dir,      # Where individual results are\n    dst_root=analysis_root_dir,      # Where combined result goes\n    overwrite=True,\n)\n</code></pre> <p>Output files: - <code>combined_cells_agg.csv</code> \u2014 All cells from all samples - <code>combined_summary.csv</code> \u2014 Summary statistics per sample</p>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#understanding-combined-output","title":"Understanding Combined Output","text":"<p><code>combined_cells_agg.csv</code>:</p> sample_id region_id region_name cell_count volume ... mouse_01 1 isocortex 1523 6.2 ... mouse_01 2 hippocampus 892 3.8 ... mouse_02 1 isocortex 1489 6.0 ... <p>Use this for: - Group comparisons (control vs. treatment) - Correlation analyses - Export to statistical software (R, Prism, etc.)</p>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#parallel-processing","title":"Parallel Processing","text":"<p>\u26a0\ufe0f Caution: Running multiple pipelines in parallel can exhaust GPU memory or disk I/O.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#option-1-sequential-processing-safer","title":"Option 1: Sequential Processing (Safer)","text":"<pre><code>for img_name in imgs_ls:\n    pipeline = Pipeline(analysis_root_dir / img_name)\n    pipeline.run_pipeline(...)  # One at a time\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#option-2-parallel-at-registration-level","title":"Option 2: Parallel at Registration Level","text":"<p>Elastix (the registration tool) can use multiple CPU cores:</p> <pre><code># In your shell before running\nexport OMP_NUM_THREADS=8  # Use 8 cores for registration\n\n# Cell counting still uses GPU but one at a time\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#option-3-separate-gpucpu-instances","title":"Option 3: Separate GPU/CPU Instances","text":"<p>If you have multiple GPUs:</p> <pre><code>import os\n\n# GPU 0\nos.environ[\"CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES\"] = \"0\"\npipeline1 = Pipeline(analysis_root_dir / \"mouse_01\")\n\n# GPU 1\nos.environ[\"CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES\"] = \"1\"\npipeline2 = Pipeline(analysis_root_dir / \"mouse_02\")\n</code></pre> <p>Note: Requires careful management \u2014 recommended for advanced users only.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#monitoring-progress","title":"Monitoring Progress","text":"<p>For long-running batches, monitor progress:</p> <pre><code>import time\nfrom datetime import datetime\n\ntotal = len(imgs_ls)\nstart_time = time.time()\n\nfor i, img_name in enumerate(imgs_ls, 1):\n    print(f\"\\n[{i}/{total}] {img_name} at {datetime.now()}\")\n\n    # ... processing ...\n\n    elapsed = time.time() - start_time\n    avg_time = elapsed / i\n    remaining = avg_time * (total - i)\n    print(f\"  ETA: {remaining/60:.1f} minutes remaining\")\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#best-practices","title":"Best Practices","text":""},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#1-start-small","title":"1. Start Small","text":"<pre><code># Test with 1-2 images first\nimgs_ls = [\"mouse_01\"]  # Just one\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#2-use-overwritefalse-initially","title":"2. Use overwrite=False Initially","text":"<pre><code>overwrite = False  # Skip existing files, safe for resuming\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#3-save-configs-with-results","title":"3. Save Configs with Results","text":"<pre><code># Config is auto-saved, but also document your choices\nwith open(analysis_root_dir / \"processing_notes.txt\", \"w\") as f:\n    f.write(\"Threshold: 60 (determined from mouse_01 tuning)\\n\")\n    f.write(\"Date: 2024-01-15\\n\")\n    f.write(\"Operator: Your Name\\n\")\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#4-verify-periodically","title":"4. Verify Periodically","text":"<pre><code># After every N images, check one result\nif i % 5 == 0:\n    vc = VisualCheck(analysis_img_dir, tuning=False)\n    vc.combine_cellc()\n    print(\"  Visual check saved \u2014 verify before continuing!\")\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/batch.html#example-complete-batch-script","title":"Example: Complete Batch Script","text":"<pre><code>\"\"\"Complete batch processing example.\"\"\"\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport traceback\nfrom cellcounter import Pipeline, VisualCheck\nfrom cellcounter.funcs.batch_combine_funcs import combine_root\n\ndef main():\n    # Configuration\n    stitched_imgs_dir = Path(\"/data/lab/stitched_imgs\")\n    analysis_root_dir = Path(\"/data/lab/analysis\")\n    overwrite = False\n\n    # Get images (or specify list)\n    imgs_ls = Pipeline.get_imgs_ls(stitched_imgs_dir)\n    print(f\"Found {len(imgs_ls)} images to process\")\n\n    # Track stats\n    successful = []\n    failed = []\n\n    for i, img_name in enumerate(imgs_ls, 1):\n        print(f\"\\n{'='*50}\")\n        print(f\"[{i}/{len(imgs_ls)}] Processing: {img_name}\")\n        print(f\"{'='*50}\")\n\n        in_fp = stitched_imgs_dir / img_name\n        analysis_img_dir = analysis_root_dir / img_name\n\n        try:\n            pipeline = Pipeline(analysis_img_dir)\n\n            # Apply standard configuration\n            pipeline.update_config(\n                chunks={\"z\": 500, \"y\": 500, \"x\": 500},\n                registration={\n                    \"ref_orientation\": {\"z\": -2, \"y\": 3, \"x\": 1},\n                    \"downsample_rough\": {\"z\": 3, \"y\": 6, \"x\": 6},\n                },\n                cell_counting={\n                    \"tophat_radius\": 10,\n                    \"threshd_value\": 60,\n                    \"min_wshed_size\": 1,\n                    \"max_wshed_size\": 700,\n                },\n            )\n\n            # Run pipeline\n            pipeline.run_pipeline(str(in_fp), overwrite=overwrite)\n\n            # Visual QC\n            vc = VisualCheck(analysis_img_dir, tuning=False)\n            vc.combine_reg(overwrite=overwrite)\n            vc.combine_cellc(overwrite=overwrite)\n\n            print(f\"\u2713 SUCCESS: {img_name}\")\n            successful.append(img_name)\n\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"\u2717 FAILED: {img_name}\")\n            print(traceback.format_exc())\n            failed.append((img_name, str(e)))\n\n    # Combine results\n    if successful:\n        print(\"\\n Combining results...\")\n        combine_root(analysis_root_dir, analysis_root_dir, overwrite=True)\n\n    # Final report\n    print(f\"\\n{'='*50}\")\n    print(\"BATCH PROCESSING COMPLETE\")\n    print(f\"{'='*50}\")\n    print(f\"Successful: {len(successful)}/{len(imgs_ls)}\")\n    print(f\"Failed: {len(failed)}/{len(imgs_ls)}\")\n\n    if failed:\n        print(\"\\nFailed images:\")\n        for name, error in failed:\n            print(f\"  - {name}: {error}\")\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n</code></pre> <p>Save as <code>batch_process.py</code> and run:</p> <pre><code>uv run python batch_process.py\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html","title":"Configuration Guide","text":"<p>Complete reference for tuning CellCounter parameters for your specific data.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#accessing-configuration","title":"Accessing Configuration","text":"<p>There are two ways to work with configuration:</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#option-1-programmatic-recommended","title":"Option 1: Programmatic (Recommended)","text":"<pre><code>from cellcounter import Pipeline\n\npipeline = Pipeline(\"/path/to/project\")\n\n# Read current values\nprint(pipeline.config.cell_counting.threshd_value)  # 60\n\n# Update and save\npipeline.update_config(\n    cell_counting={\"threshd_value\": 45}\n)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#option-2-edit-configjson-directly","title":"Option 2: Edit config.json Directly","text":"<pre><code># Open in your favorite editor\nnano /path/to/project/config.json\n</code></pre> <p>Changes take effect immediately \u2014 no restart needed.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#configuration-structure","title":"Configuration Structure","text":"<pre><code>class ProjConfig:\n    # Zarr chunking\n    chunks: DimsConfig              # How image is split for processing\n\n    # Tuning crop region\n    tuning_trim: DimsSliceConfig    # Small crop for parameter tuning\n\n    # Nested configuration sections\n    cluster: ClusterConfig          # Dask parallel computing settings\n    reference: ReferenceConfig      # Atlas reference settings\n    registration: RegistrationConfig # Image alignment parameters\n    cell_counting: CellCountingConfig # Cell detection parameters\n    visual_check: VisualCheckConfig  # Visualization settings\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#chunks-configuration","title":"Chunks Configuration","text":"<p>Control how your image is divided for parallel processing.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#why-chunks-matter","title":"Why Chunks Matter","text":"Chunk Size Memory Usage Speed Best For Small (100\u00b3) Low Slower (more overhead) Limited RAM Medium (500\u00b3) Moderate Fast Most users (default) Large (1000\u00b3) High Faster (less overhead) High RAM + GPU"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#example-configurations","title":"Example Configurations","text":"<pre><code># Ultra-large images with GPU (16GB+ VRAM)\nchunks={\"z\": 1000, \"y\": 1000, \"x\": 1000}\n\n# Standard whole-brain lightsheet (default, recommended)\nchunks={\"z\": 500, \"y\": 500, \"x\": 500}\n\n# Limited RAM / CPU-only (&lt; 32GB RAM)\nchunks={\"z\": 250, \"y\": 250, \"x\": 250}\n\n# Very limited RAM (laptop, test images)\nchunks={\"z\": 128, \"y\": 128, \"x\": 128}\n</code></pre> <p>Chunk Size Rules</p> <ul> <li>Must evenly divide your image dimensions OR</li> <li>CellCounter will pad automatically (slight overhead)</li> <li>Larger chunks = fewer files = faster I/O</li> <li>Smaller chunks = less memory per worker</li> </ul>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#registration-configuration","title":"Registration Configuration","text":"<p>Control how your image is aligned to the Allen Atlas.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#image-orientation-ref_orientation","title":"Image Orientation (<code>ref_orientation</code>)","text":"<p>Maps your image axes to the atlas coordinate system:</p> <pre><code>registration={\n    \"ref_orientation\": {\"z\": -2, \"y\": 3, \"x\": 1}\n}\n</code></pre> <p>Understanding the values: - Positive (1, 2, 3): Use axis 1, 2, or 3 without flipping - Negative (-1, -2, -3): Use axis 1, 2, or 3 AND flip it</p> <p>The Allen Atlas axes are: - Z: Inferior \u2192 Superior - Y: Anterior \u2192 Posterior - X: Left \u2192 Right</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#common-orientation-patterns","title":"Common Orientation Patterns","text":"<p>Your image axes depend on your microscope and how the sample was mounted. Check with napari:</p> <pre><code>import napari\nimport tifffile\n\nviewer = napari.Viewer()\nviewer.add_image(tifffile.imread(\"your_image.tiff\"))\nnapari.run()\n</code></pre> <p>Look at voxel coordinates in napari to determine orientation:</p> Your Image Atlas Orientation Setting z=0 at bottom z=0 at bottom <code>{\"z\": 1, ...}</code> z=0 at top z=0 at bottom <code>{\"z\": -1, ...}</code> x=left, y=anterior standard <code>{\"z\": 1, \"y\": 2, \"x\": 3}</code>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#finding-your-orientation","title":"Finding Your Orientation","text":"<p>Method 1: Trial and Error <pre><code># Try different orientations, check registration result\npipeline.update_config(\n    registration={\"ref_orientation\": {\"z\": -2, \"y\": 3, \"x\": 1}}\n)\npipeline.reg_elastix(overwrite=True)\n\n# Visual check\nvc.combine_reg()  # Compare trimmed vs ref vs registered\n</code></pre></p> <p>Method 2: Compare Dimensions <pre><code>import tifffile\nimport numpy as np\n\nimg = tifffile.imread(\"your_image.tiff\")\nref = tifffile.imread(\"~/.cellcounter/atlas/average_template_25.tif\")\n\nprint(f\"Your image: {img.shape}\")  # e.g., (300, 2048, 2048)\nprint(f\"Atlas:      {ref.shape}\")  # e.g., (528, 320, 456)\n\n# Match roughly: 300 z-slices \u2248 528 atlas z-slices\n# So your z maps to atlas z, likely {'z': ...}\n</code></pre></p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#downsampling","title":"Downsampling","text":"<p>Downsample your high-resolution image to match atlas resolution (~25\u00b5m).</p> <pre><code>registration={\n    # Integer stride (fast, first pass)\n    \"downsample_rough\": {\"z\": 3, \"y\": 6, \"x\": 6},\n\n    # Float factor (slow, precise, second pass)\n    \"downsample_fine\": {\"z\": 1.0, \"y\": 0.6, \"x\": 0.6},\n}\n</code></pre> <p>Calculate based on your voxel size:</p> Your Resolution Rough Fine Result 1 \u00b5m (lightsheet) (2, 4, 4) (1.0, 0.6, 0.6) ~25\u00b5m 2 \u00b5m (1, 3, 3) (1.0, 0.8, 0.8) ~25\u00b5m 5 \u00b5m (1, 2, 2) (1.0, 1.0, 1.0) ~25\u00b5m <p>Formula: <code>your_resolution \u00d7 rough \u00d7 fine \u2248 25</code></p> <p>Registration Failing?</p> <p>If elastix fails to converge, try: 1. Different <code>downsample_rough</code> factors 2. Adjusting <code>reg_trim</code> to focus on brain region 3. Changing <code>lower_bound</code> / <code>upper_bound</code> intensity clipping</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#intensity-clipping","title":"Intensity Clipping","text":"<pre><code>registration={\n    \"lower_bound\": 100,        # Pixels below this become...\n    \"lower_bound_mapto\": 0,    # ...this value\n    \"upper_bound\": 5000,       # Pixels above this become...\n    \"upper_bound_mapto\": 5000, # ...this value\n}\n</code></pre> <p>Adjust based on your image histogram: - lower_bound: Background level (exclude dark regions) - upper_bound: Saturation level (exclude saturated regions)</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#cell-counting-configuration","title":"Cell Counting Configuration","text":"<p>Control how cells are detected and segmented.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#detection-sensitivity-threshd_value","title":"Detection Sensitivity (<code>threshd_value</code>)","text":"<p>Most important parameter! Controls how bright a voxel must be to be considered \"cell\":</p> <pre><code>cell_counting={\n    \"threshd_value\": 60  # Default\n}\n</code></pre> Threshold Result When to Use 20-40 Many cells detected, more false positives High SNR, dim cells 50-70 Balanced (default) Standard cFos staining 80-120 Fewer cells, cleaner Bright staining, want conservative <p>Finding the Right Threshold</p> <ol> <li>Run tuning with default (60)</li> <li>Visualize with <code>vc.combine_cellc()</code></li> <li>If too many debris detected \u2192 increase threshold</li> <li>If cells being missed \u2192 decrease threshold</li> <li>Iterate in steps of 10-20</li> </ol>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#background-removal-tophat_radius","title":"Background Removal (<code>tophat_radius</code>)","text":"<p>Removes large-scale illumination variations:</p> <pre><code>cell_counting={\n    \"tophat_radius\": 10  # Default, in voxels\n}\n</code></pre> <ul> <li>Smaller (5-8): Better for small cells, uneven background</li> <li>Larger (12-20): Better for large cells, smooth background</li> <li>Too large: Removes actual cell signal</li> </ul> <p>Visual test: After <code>tophat_filter</code>, the background should be uniform gray with cells standing out.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#edge-enhancement-dog_sigma1-dog_sigma2","title":"Edge Enhancement (<code>dog_sigma1</code>, <code>dog_sigma2</code>)","text":"<p>Difference of Gaussians highlights cell-like structures:</p> <pre><code>cell_counting={\n    \"dog_sigma1\": 1,  # Inner Gaussian (cell center)\n    \"dog_sigma2\": 4,  # Outer Gaussian (background)\n}\n</code></pre> <ul> <li>sigma1: Roughly cell radius in voxels (typical cell ~3-5 voxels)</li> <li>sigma2: 3-4 \u00d7 sigma1 (captures background around cell)</li> </ul> <p>Adjust based on cell size: - Small cells (fine resolution): <code>sigma1=0.5, sigma2=2</code> - Medium cells (default): <code>sigma1=1, sigma2=4</code> - Large cells (thick slices): <code>sigma1=2, sigma2=6</code></p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#adaptive-thresholding-large_gauss_radius","title":"Adaptive Thresholding (<code>large_gauss_radius</code>)","text":"<pre><code>cell_counting={\n    \"large_gauss_radius\": 101  # Default\n}\n</code></pre> <p>Large Gaussian subtraction for local contrast enhancement. Usually doesn't need adjustment.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#cell-size-filters","title":"Cell Size Filters","text":"<p>Filter objects by voxel count to remove debris and clusters:</p> <pre><code>cell_counting={\n    # First filter (on thresholded objects)\n    \"min_threshd_size\": 100,   # Minimum connected component\n    \"max_threshd_size\": 9000,  # Maximum (prevents huge clusters)\n\n    # Second filter (on watershed segments)\n    \"min_wshed_size\": 1,       # Minimum final cell size\n    \"max_wshed_size\": 700,     # Maximum final cell size\n}\n</code></pre> <p>Size guidelines (assume 1\u00b5m voxels):</p> Cell Type Min Size Max Size cFos+ nuclei 10-50 300-500 Neurons 100-200 500-1000 Large cells 200-500 1000-2000 <p>Finding Size Range</p> <ol> <li>Look at your raw image in napari</li> <li>Measure typical cell diameter</li> <li>Calculate volume: 4/3 \u00d7 \u03c0 \u00d7 r\u00b3</li> <li>Set min/max ~50% around this</li> </ol>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#maxima-detection-maxima_radius","title":"Maxima Detection (<code>maxima_radius</code>)","text":"<pre><code>cell_counting={\n    \"maxima_radius\": 10  # Default, in voxels\n}\n</code></pre> <p>Radius for local maxima detection (cell center identification).</p> <ul> <li>Smaller: More sensitive, may split single cells</li> <li>Larger: Less sensitive, may merge nearby cells</li> <li>Default works for most: 10 voxels (~10\u00b5m)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#cluster-configuration","title":"Cluster Configuration","text":"<p>Control Dask parallel computing resources.</p> <pre><code>cluster={\n    \"heavy_n_workers\": 1,           # For memory-intensive ops\n    \"heavy_threads_per_worker\": 6,  # Threads per heavy worker\n    \"busy_n_workers\": 4,            # For I/O-bound ops\n    \"busy_threads_per_worker\": 1,   # Threads per busy worker\n}\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#cluster-types-used","title":"Cluster Types Used","text":"Cluster Method Workers Use Case GPU <code>gpu_cluster()</code> 1 Cell counting with CuPy Heavy <code>heavy_cluster()</code> 1 Watershed (high memory) Busy <code>busy_cluster()</code> 4 I/O, registration, mapping"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#adjusting-for-your-hardware","title":"Adjusting for Your Hardware","text":"<p>High-end workstation (64GB+ RAM, GPU): <pre><code>cluster={\n    \"heavy_n_workers\": 2,\n    \"heavy_threads_per_worker\": 8,\n    \"busy_n_workers\": 8,\n}\n</code></pre></p> <p>Laptop / Limited RAM (16GB): <pre><code>cluster={\n    \"heavy_n_workers\": 1,\n    \"heavy_threads_per_worker\": 2,\n    \"busy_n_workers\": 2,\n}\n</code></pre></p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#tuning-configuration","title":"Tuning Configuration","text":"<p>Define the crop region for parameter tuning.</p> <pre><code>tuning_trim={\n    \"z\": {\"start\": 700, \"stop\": 800, \"step\": None},\n    \"y\": {\"start\": 1000, \"stop\": 3000, \"step\": None},\n    \"x\": {\"start\": 1000, \"stop\": 3000, \"step\": None},\n}\n</code></pre> <p>Choose a region that: - Contains cells typical of your data - Has some background (not all cells) - Is representative (not edge artifacts) - Runs quickly (smaller = faster iteration)</p> <p>Recommended sizes: - Z: 50-200 slices (depending on z-resolution) - Y, X: 1000-4000 pixels each</p>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#visual-check-configuration","title":"Visual Check Configuration","text":"<p>Control visualization outputs.</p> <pre><code>visual_check={\n    \"heatmap_raw_radius\": 5,    # Raw coordinate heatmap sphere size\n    \"heatmap_trfm_radius\": 3,   # Transformed heatmap sphere size\n}\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#configuration-recipes","title":"Configuration Recipes","text":""},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#recipe-1-high-resolution-lightsheet-1m","title":"Recipe 1: High-Resolution Lightsheet (1\u00b5m)","text":"<pre><code>pipeline.update_config(\n    chunks={\"z\": 500, \"y\": 500, \"x\": 500},\n    registration={\n        \"ref_orientation\": {\"z\": -2, \"y\": 3, \"x\": 1},\n        \"downsample_rough\": {\"z\": 2, \"y\": 4, \"x\": 4},\n        \"downsample_fine\": {\"z\": 1.0, \"y\": 0.6, \"x\": 0.6},\n    },\n    cell_counting={\n        \"tophat_radius\": 10,\n        \"dog_sigma1\": 1,\n        \"dog_sigma2\": 4,\n        \"threshd_value\": 60,\n        \"min_wshed_size\": 50,\n        \"max_wshed_size\": 500,\n    },\n)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#recipe-2-lower-resolution-5m","title":"Recipe 2: Lower Resolution (5\u00b5m)","text":"<pre><code>pipeline.update_config(\n    registration={\n        \"downsample_rough\": {\"z\": 1, \"y\": 2, \"x\": 2},\n        \"downsample_fine\": {\"z\": 1.0, \"y\": 1.0, \"x\": 1.0},\n    },\n    cell_counting={\n        \"tophat_radius\": 5,\n        \"dog_sigma1\": 0.5,\n        \"dog_sigma2\": 2,\n        \"threshd_value\": 50,\n        \"min_wshed_size\": 10,\n        \"max_wshed_size\": 200,\n    },\n)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#recipe-3-conservative-detection-fewer-false-positives","title":"Recipe 3: Conservative Detection (Fewer False Positives)","text":"<pre><code>pipeline.update_config(\n    cell_counting={\n        \"threshd_value\": 80,       # Higher threshold\n        \"min_wshed_size\": 100,     # Larger minimum\n        \"tophat_radius\": 12,       # More background removal\n    },\n)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#recipe-4-sensitive-detection-more-cells-some-false-positives","title":"Recipe 4: Sensitive Detection (More Cells, Some False Positives)","text":"<pre><code>pipeline.update_config(\n    cell_counting={\n        \"threshd_value\": 40,       # Lower threshold\n        \"min_wshed_size\": 10,      # Smaller minimum\n        \"tophat_radius\": 8,        # Less background removal\n    },\n)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#saving-and-loading-configurations","title":"Saving and Loading Configurations","text":""},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#save-for-reuse","title":"Save for Reuse","text":"<pre><code># Save to file for reuse across projects\nimport json\n\nconfig = pipeline.config\nwith open(\"my_settings.json\", \"w\") as f:\n    json.dump(config.model_dump(), f, indent=2)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/configuration.html#load-settings","title":"Load Settings","text":"<pre><code>import json\nfrom cellcounter.models.proj_config import ProjConfig\n\n# Load saved settings\nwith open(\"my_settings.json\") as f:\n    settings = json.load(f)\n\n# Apply to new project\nnew_pipeline = Pipeline(\"/new/project\")\nnew_pipeline.update_config(**settings)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html","title":"Visual Quality Control","text":"<p>Verify that registration and cell detection are working correctly by visualizing intermediate and final outputs.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#why-visual-qc-matters","title":"Why Visual QC Matters","text":"<p>Even with good parameters, always verify:</p> <ol> <li>Registration accuracy \u2014 Is your image aligned to the atlas?</li> <li>Cell detection quality \u2014 Are real cells being found?</li> <li>False positive rate \u2014 Is debris being counted as cells?</li> <li>Cell separation \u2014 Are touching cells split correctly?</li> </ol> <p>Golden Rule</p> <p>Visualize your results before trusting the CSV numbers. A few minutes of QC can save hours of reprocessing.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#tools-for-visualization","title":"Tools for Visualization","text":""},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#napari-recommended","title":"napari (Recommended)","text":"<pre><code># napari is included with CellCounter\nuv run napari\n</code></pre> <p>Or from Python:</p> <pre><code>import napari\nimport tifffile\n\nviewer = napari.Viewer()\nviewer.add_image(tifffile.imread(\"your_file.tiff\"))\nnapari.run()\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#imagejfiji","title":"ImageJ/Fiji","text":"<p>Standard bioimage analysis tool. Open TIFF files directly.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#python-quick-checks","title":"Python (Quick Checks)","text":"<pre><code>import tifffile\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\nimg = tifffile.imread(\"image.tiff\")\nplt.imshow(img[100])  # View z-slice 100\nplt.show()\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#checking-registration","title":"Checking Registration","text":"<p>Registration aligns your image to the Allen Atlas. Verify it's correct!</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#generate-registration-overlay","title":"Generate Registration Overlay","text":"<pre><code>from cellcounter import VisualCheck\n\nvc = VisualCheck(\"/path/to/project\", tuning=False)\nvc.combine_reg()  # Creates combined_reg.tiff\n</code></pre> <p>This creates a 3-channel TIFF: - Channel 0 (Red): Your trimmed/bounded image - Channel 1 (Green): Reference atlas - Channel 2 (Blue): Registered image</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#what-to-look-for","title":"What to Look For","text":"<p>Open <code>combined_reg.tiff</code> in napari:</p> <pre><code>import napari\nimport tifffile\n\nimg = tifffile.imread(\"cellcount/combined_reg.tiff\")\nviewer = napari.Viewer()\nviewer.add_image(img, channel_axis=0, name=[\"trimmed\", \"reference\", \"registered\"])\nnapari.run()\n</code></pre> <p>Tick the visibility (eye icon) of each channel to compare:</p> Check Good Bad Brain outline matches \u2713 Contours align \u2717 Brain shape wrong Major structures \u2713 Hippocampus, cortex aligned \u2717 Structures don't overlap Ventricles \u2713 Dark regions align \u2717 Ventricles offset"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#troubleshooting-registration","title":"Troubleshooting Registration","text":"<p>Issue: Registration is flipped - Check <code>ref_orientation</code> \u2014 one or more axes may need negation - Example: <code>{\"z\": -2, \"y\": 3, \"x\": 1}</code> instead of <code>{\"z\": 2, ...}</code></p> <p>Issue: Registration is rotated 90\u00b0 - Swap y and x in orientation: <code>{\"z\": 1, \"y\": 3, \"x\": 2}</code></p> <p>Issue: Brain not centered - Adjust <code>reg_trim</code> to crop to brain region - Check <code>downsample_rough</code> values match your resolution</p> <p>Issue: Registration failed/strange warping - Adjust intensity bounds (<code>lower_bound</code>, <code>upper_bound</code>) - Try different downsampling factors - Ensure reference atlas downloaded correctly (<code>cellcounter-init</code>)</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#checking-cell-detection","title":"Checking Cell Detection","text":""},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#generate-cell-counting-overlay","title":"Generate Cell Counting Overlay","text":"<pre><code>from cellcounter import VisualCheck\n\n# For tuning crop (faster)\nvc_tuning = VisualCheck(\"/path/to/project\", tuning=True)\nvc_tuning.combine_cellc()  # Creates cellcount/tuning/combined_cellc.tiff\n\n# For full image (slower, creates trimmed view)\nvc_full = VisualCheck(\"/path/to/project\", tuning=False)\nvc_full.combine_cellc()    # Creates cellcount/combined_cellc.tiff\n</code></pre> <p>This creates a 3-channel TIFF: - Channel 0 (Gray): Raw image (intensity-scaled) - Channel 1 (Blue): Thresholded mask (filtered objects) - Channel 2 (Green): Final detected cells</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#interpreting-the-overlay","title":"Interpreting the Overlay","text":"<pre><code>import napari\nimport tifffile\n\nimg = tifffile.imread(\"cellcount/tuning/combined_cellc.tiff\")\nviewer = napari.Viewer()\nviewer.add_image(img, channel_axis=0,\n                 name=[\"raw\", \"thresholded\", \"cells\"],\n                 colormap=[\"gray\", \"blue\", \"green\"])\nnapari.run()\n</code></pre> <p>What each channel shows:</p> Channel Shows What to Check Raw Original fluorescence Good SNR, no artifacts Thresholded Objects passing size filters Reasonable shapes, no holes Cells Final watershed segments One segment per cell"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#sign-of-good-detection","title":"Sign of Good Detection","text":"<p>\u2713 Green regions (cells) align with bright spots in raw \u2713 **Each bright spot has one green segment \u2713 Green segments are roughly circular/oval \u2713 No tiny debris included (check size filter settings)</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#common-cell-detection-problems","title":"Common Cell Detection Problems","text":""},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#problem-missing-cells","title":"Problem: Missing Cells","text":"<p>Symptoms: Bright spots in raw have no green overlay</p> <p>Causes &amp; Solutions:</p> Cause Solution Threshold too high Lower <code>threshd_value</code> (60 \u2192 40) Size filter too large Decrease <code>min_wshed_size</code> Background not removed Increase <code>tophat_radius</code> Cells too dim Check image intensity scale"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#problem-too-many-false-positives","title":"Problem: Too Many False Positives","text":"<p>Symptoms: Green regions on dim background, debris</p> <p>Causes &amp; Solutions:</p> Cause Solution Threshold too low Raise <code>threshd_value</code> (60 \u2192 80) Size filter too small Increase <code>min_wshed_size</code> Debris not filtered Adjust <code>min_threshd_size</code>, <code>max_threshd_size</code>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#problem-touching-cells-merged","title":"Problem: Touching Cells Merged","text":"<p>Symptoms: One green region covers multiple bright spots</p> <p>Solutions: - Adjust <code>dog_sigma1</code> and <code>dog_sigma2</code> for better edge detection - Check <code>maxima_radius</code> \u2014 may be too large - Verify watershed is running (check for <code>wshed_labels</code> file)</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#problem-cells-split-incorrectly","title":"Problem: Cells Split Incorrectly","text":"<p>Symptoms: Single cell has multiple green regions</p> <p>Solutions: - Increase <code>maxima_radius</code> to avoid over-splitting - Adjust <code>dog_sigma1</code> closer to actual cell radius - Check if <code>min_wshed_size</code> is fragmenting cells</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#checking-cell-to-region-mapping","title":"Checking Cell-to-Region Mapping","text":"<p>Verify cells are correctly mapped to brain regions.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#generate-heatmaps","title":"Generate Heatmaps","text":"<pre><code>from cellcounter import VisualCheck\n\nvc = VisualCheck(\"/path/to/project\", tuning=False)\n\n# Raw coordinates heatmap\nvc.coords2heatmap_raw()        # cellcount/heatmap_raw.tiff\nvc.combine_heatmap_raw()       # cellcount/combined_heatmap_raw.tiff\n\n# Transformed coordinates heatmap\nvc.coords2heatmap_trfm()       # cellcount/heatmap_trfm.tiff\nvc.combine_heatmap_trfm()      # cellcount/combined_heatmap_trfm.tiff\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#interpreting-heatmaps","title":"Interpreting Heatmaps","text":"<p>Raw Heatmap: Cell density in original image space <pre><code>img = tifffile.imread(\"cellcount/combined_heatmap_raw.tiff\")\n# Channels: raw image, thresholded, heatmap\n</code></pre></p> <p>Transformed Heatmap: Cell density in atlas space <pre><code>img = tifffile.imread(\"cellcount/combined_heatmap_trfm.tiff\")\n# Channels: reference, annotation, heatmap\n</code></pre></p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#what-to-check","title":"What to Check","text":"<ol> <li>Density matches expectation: High cFos in expected regions?</li> <li>No off-brain cells: Cells should fall within brain boundaries</li> <li>Smooth distribution: Hotspots should align with anatomical regions</li> </ol>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#troubleshooting-mapping","title":"Troubleshooting Mapping","text":"<p>Cells outside brain boundary: - Registration failed \u2014 check <code>combined_reg.tiff</code> - Intensity clipping too aggressive \u2014 adjust bounds</p> <p>Cells mapped to wrong regions: - Registration misalignment \u2014 re-run registration - Coordinate transform error \u2014 check <code>transform_coords</code> output</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#step-by-step-qc-workflow","title":"Step-by-Step QC Workflow","text":""},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#after-registration","title":"After Registration","text":"<pre><code># 1. Generate and view registration\nvc = VisualCheck(\"/path/to/project\", tuning=False)\nvc.combine_reg()\n\n# Open in napari and verify\n# - Brain outlines match\n# - Major structures align\n# - No obvious flipping/rotation\n</code></pre> <p>\u2713 If good: Proceed to cell detection \u2717 If bad: Adjust orientation, re-run registration</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#after-tuning","title":"After Tuning","text":"<pre><code># 2. Generate cell counting view on tuning crop\nvc = VisualCheck(\"/path/to/project\", tuning=True)\nvc.combine_cellc()\n\n# Open in napari and verify\n# - Cells are detected (green overlay on bright spots)\n# - Cells are separated correctly\n# - No obvious false positives\n</code></pre> <p>\u2713 If good: Proceed to full image \u2717 If bad: Adjust cell counting parameters, re-run tuning</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#after-full-pipeline","title":"After Full Pipeline","text":"<pre><code># 3. Check final result\nvc = VisualCheck(\"/path/to/project\", tuning=False)\nvc.combine_cellc()  # May be large, trimmed automatically\n\n# 4. Check mapping (transformed space)\nvc.combine_heatmap_trfm()\n\n# Open both and verify final outputs\n</code></pre> <p>\u2713 If good: Analysis complete! \u2717 If bad: Identify problem (detection vs registration) and re-run relevant steps</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#viewing-pipeline-intermediates","title":"Viewing Pipeline Intermediates","text":"<p>Sometimes you need to check intermediate files. Use the viewer template:</p> <pre><code>\"\"\"View any intermediate files.\"\"\"\nfrom cellcounter.models.fp_models import get_proj_fp\nfrom cellcounter.utils.viewer import view_images\n\nproj_dir = \"/path/to/your/project\"\ntuning = False\n\npfm = get_proj_fp(proj_dir, tuning=tuning)\n\n# Pick which files to view\nview_images(\n    imgs_fp_ls=[\n        # Raw and registration\n        pfm.raw,\n        # pfm.downsmpl1,\n        # pfm.downsmpl2,\n        # pfm.trimmed,\n        # pfm.bounded,\n        # pfm.regresult,\n\n        # Cell counting intermediates\n        pfm.bgrm,        # After top-hat filter\n        pfm.dog,         # After DoG filter\n        pfm.threshd,     # After threshold\n        pfm.threshd_volumes,  # After size filter\n        pfm.maxima,      # Detected maxima\n        pfm.wshed_volumes,    # After watershed\n        pfm.wshed_filt,  # Final filtered cells\n    ],\n    trimmer=(\n        slice(500, 510),    # Z range\n        slice(1500, 3000),  # Y range\n        slice(1500, 3000),  # X range\n    ),\n)\n</code></pre> <p>This opens all selected files in napari with linked views.</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#automated-qc-checklist","title":"Automated QC Checklist","text":"<p>Use this checklist for each sample:</p> Step Check Pass Criteria Registration <code>combined_reg.tiff</code> Brain outline matches atlas Detection (tuning) <code>combined_cellc.tiff</code> (tuning) &gt;80% of cells detected Detection (full) <code>combined_cellc.tiff</code> (full) Consistent with tuning Mapping <code>combined_heatmap_trfm.tiff</code> Cells in expected regions Output <code>cells_agg.csv</code> Reasonable cell counts"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#exporting-qc-images","title":"Exporting QC Images","text":"<p>For publications or documentation, export QC images:</p> <pre><code>import napari\nimport tifffile\nfrom napari.utils.io import imsave\n\n# Load data\nimg = tifffile.imread(\"cellcount/tuning/combined_cellc.tiff\")\n\n# Create viewer\nviewer = napari.Viewer()\nviewer.add_image(img, channel_axis=0)\n\n# Adjust contrast, zoom to region of interest\nviewer.camera.zoom = 2\n\n# Screenshot\nscreenshot = viewer.screenshot()\nimsave(\"qc_cell_detection.png\", screenshot)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#tips-for-large-images","title":"Tips for Large Images","text":"<p>Full-resolution images are too large to view entirely. Strategies:</p>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#1-view-crop-regions","title":"1. View Crop Regions","text":"<pre><code>import tifffile\nimport napari\n\nzarr_arr = tifffile.imread(\"cellcount/raw.zarr\")\n# Load only a region\nregion = zarr_arr[500:510, 1500:3000, 1500:3000]\n\nviewer = napari.Viewer()\nviewer.add_image(region)\nnapari.run()\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#2-use-downsampled-versions","title":"2. Use Downsampled Versions","text":"<pre><code># View downsampled registration images\ndownsmpl = tifffile.imread(\"cellcount/downsmpl2.tiff\")\n# Much smaller than raw!\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"how-to/visual-check.html#3-visual-check-auto-trims","title":"3. Visual Check Auto-Trims","text":"<p>The <code>combine_cellc()</code> method automatically trims for full images:</p> <pre><code>vc = VisualCheck(\"/path/to/project\", tuning=False)\nvc.combine_cellc()\n# Reads trim settings from config.visual_check.cellcount_trim\n</code></pre> <p>Adjust in config if needed:</p> <pre><code>pipeline.update_config(\n    combine={\n        \"cellcount_trim\": {\n            \"z\": {\"start\": 750, \"stop\": 760, \"step\": None},\n            \"y\": {\"start\": None, \"stop\": None, \"step\": None},\n            \"x\": {\"start\": None, \"stop\": None, \"step\": None},\n        }\n    }\n)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/abstract-pipeline.html","title":"Abstract Pipeline API","text":""},{"location":"reference/abstract-pipeline.html#cellcounter.pipeline.abstract_pipeline.AbstractPipeline","title":"<code>cellcounter.pipeline.abstract_pipeline.AbstractPipeline</code>","text":"<p>               Bases: <code>ABC</code></p> <p>Base class for pipeline operations with GPU/CPU switching.</p> <p>Provides: - Runtime GPU/CPU mode switching via set_gpu() - Dask cluster factories (heavy, busy, GPU) - Config and filepath model access</p> <p>Attributes:</p> Name Type Description <code>cellc_funcs</code> <code>CpuCellcFuncs</code> <p>Cell counting functions (CPU or GPU backend).</p> <code>pfm</code> <code>ProjFp</code> <p>Project filepath model.</p> <code>config</code> <code>ProjConfig</code> <p>Project configuration.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/abstract_pipeline.py</code> <pre><code>class AbstractPipeline(ABC):\n    \"\"\"Base class for pipeline operations with GPU/CPU switching.\n\n    Provides:\n    - Runtime GPU/CPU mode switching via set_gpu()\n    - Dask cluster factories (heavy, busy, GPU)\n    - Config and filepath model access\n\n    Attributes:\n        cellc_funcs: Cell counting functions (CPU or GPU backend).\n        pfm: Project filepath model.\n        config: Project configuration.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    cellc_funcs: CpuCellcFuncs\n    _gpu_cluster: Callable[..., SpecCluster]\n    _tuning: bool\n    _pfm: ProjFp\n\n    def __init__(self, proj_dir: Path | str, *, tuning: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Initialize pipeline with project directory.\n\n        Args:\n            proj_dir: Path to project directory.\n            tuning: If True, use tuning subdirectory for parameters.\n        \"\"\"\n        self._tuning = tuning\n        self._pfm = get_proj_fp(proj_dir, tuning=tuning)\n        self.set_gpu(enabled=True)\n\n    @property\n    def pfm(self) -&gt; ProjFp:\n        \"\"\"Project filepath model.\"\"\"\n        return self._pfm\n\n    @property\n    def tuning(self) -&gt; bool:\n        \"\"\"Is project in tuning version or raw version.\"\"\"\n        return self._tuning\n\n    @property\n    def config(self) -&gt; ProjConfig:\n        \"\"\"Project configuration (cached on pfm).\"\"\"\n        return self._pfm.config\n\n    def update_config(self, updates: dict) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Update project configuration with new values.\n\n        Args:\n            updates: Key-value pairs to update in config.\n        \"\"\"\n        ProjConfig.ensure(self._pfm.config_fp, updates)\n\n    def heavy_cluster(self) -&gt; SpecCluster:\n        \"\"\"Create cluster with few workers and high memory per worker.\n\n        Use for memory-intensive operations like watershed.\n        \"\"\"\n        return LocalCluster(\n            n_workers=self.config.cluster.heavy_n_workers,\n            threads_per_worker=self.config.cluster.heavy_threads_per_worker,\n        )\n\n    def busy_cluster(self) -&gt; SpecCluster:\n        \"\"\"Create cluster with many workers and low memory per worker.\n\n        Use for I/O-bound or parallel operations.\n        \"\"\"\n        return LocalCluster(\n            n_workers=self.config.cluster.busy_n_workers,\n            threads_per_worker=self.config.cluster.busy_threads_per_worker,\n        )\n\n    def gpu_cluster(self) -&gt; SpecCluster:\n        \"\"\"Create GPU-enabled cluster for CUDA operations.\n\n        Falls back to CPU cluster if CUDA unavailable.\n        \"\"\"\n        return self._gpu_cluster()\n\n    def set_gpu(self, *, enabled: bool = True) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Switch between GPU and CPU mode at runtime.\n\n        Args:\n            enabled: True for GPU mode, False for CPU mode.\n        \"\"\"\n        if enabled:\n            self._gpu_cluster = _get_gpu_cluster_factory()\n            self.cellc_funcs = _get_cellc_funcs()\n        else:\n            self._gpu_cluster = lambda: LocalCluster(n_workers=2, threads_per_worker=1)\n            self.cellc_funcs = CpuCellcFuncs()\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/abstract-pipeline.html#cellcounter.pipeline.abstract_pipeline.AbstractPipeline.config","title":"<code>config</code>  <code>property</code>","text":"<p>Project configuration (cached on pfm).</p>"},{"location":"reference/abstract-pipeline.html#cellcounter.pipeline.abstract_pipeline.AbstractPipeline.pfm","title":"<code>pfm</code>  <code>property</code>","text":"<p>Project filepath model.</p>"},{"location":"reference/abstract-pipeline.html#cellcounter.pipeline.abstract_pipeline.AbstractPipeline.tuning","title":"<code>tuning</code>  <code>property</code>","text":"<p>Is project in tuning version or raw version.</p>"},{"location":"reference/abstract-pipeline.html#cellcounter.pipeline.abstract_pipeline.AbstractPipeline.__init__","title":"<code>__init__(proj_dir, *, tuning=False)</code>","text":"<p>Initialize pipeline with project directory.</p> <p>Parameters:</p> Name Type Description Default <code>proj_dir</code> <code>Path | str</code> <p>Path to project directory.</p> required <code>tuning</code> <code>bool</code> <p>If True, use tuning subdirectory for parameters.</p> <code>False</code> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/abstract_pipeline.py</code> <pre><code>def __init__(self, proj_dir: Path | str, *, tuning: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Initialize pipeline with project directory.\n\n    Args:\n        proj_dir: Path to project directory.\n        tuning: If True, use tuning subdirectory for parameters.\n    \"\"\"\n    self._tuning = tuning\n    self._pfm = get_proj_fp(proj_dir, tuning=tuning)\n    self.set_gpu(enabled=True)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/abstract-pipeline.html#cellcounter.pipeline.abstract_pipeline.AbstractPipeline.busy_cluster","title":"<code>busy_cluster()</code>","text":"<p>Create cluster with many workers and low memory per worker.</p> <p>Use for I/O-bound or parallel operations.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/abstract_pipeline.py</code> <pre><code>def busy_cluster(self) -&gt; SpecCluster:\n    \"\"\"Create cluster with many workers and low memory per worker.\n\n    Use for I/O-bound or parallel operations.\n    \"\"\"\n    return LocalCluster(\n        n_workers=self.config.cluster.busy_n_workers,\n        threads_per_worker=self.config.cluster.busy_threads_per_worker,\n    )\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/abstract-pipeline.html#cellcounter.pipeline.abstract_pipeline.AbstractPipeline.gpu_cluster","title":"<code>gpu_cluster()</code>","text":"<p>Create GPU-enabled cluster for CUDA operations.</p> <p>Falls back to CPU cluster if CUDA unavailable.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/abstract_pipeline.py</code> <pre><code>def gpu_cluster(self) -&gt; SpecCluster:\n    \"\"\"Create GPU-enabled cluster for CUDA operations.\n\n    Falls back to CPU cluster if CUDA unavailable.\n    \"\"\"\n    return self._gpu_cluster()\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/abstract-pipeline.html#cellcounter.pipeline.abstract_pipeline.AbstractPipeline.heavy_cluster","title":"<code>heavy_cluster()</code>","text":"<p>Create cluster with few workers and high memory per worker.</p> <p>Use for memory-intensive operations like watershed.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/abstract_pipeline.py</code> <pre><code>def heavy_cluster(self) -&gt; SpecCluster:\n    \"\"\"Create cluster with few workers and high memory per worker.\n\n    Use for memory-intensive operations like watershed.\n    \"\"\"\n    return LocalCluster(\n        n_workers=self.config.cluster.heavy_n_workers,\n        threads_per_worker=self.config.cluster.heavy_threads_per_worker,\n    )\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/abstract-pipeline.html#cellcounter.pipeline.abstract_pipeline.AbstractPipeline.set_gpu","title":"<code>set_gpu(*, enabled=True)</code>","text":"<p>Switch between GPU and CPU mode at runtime.</p> <p>Parameters:</p> Name Type Description Default <code>enabled</code> <code>bool</code> <p>True for GPU mode, False for CPU mode.</p> <code>True</code> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/abstract_pipeline.py</code> <pre><code>def set_gpu(self, *, enabled: bool = True) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Switch between GPU and CPU mode at runtime.\n\n    Args:\n        enabled: True for GPU mode, False for CPU mode.\n    \"\"\"\n    if enabled:\n        self._gpu_cluster = _get_gpu_cluster_factory()\n        self.cellc_funcs = _get_cellc_funcs()\n    else:\n        self._gpu_cluster = lambda: LocalCluster(n_workers=2, threads_per_worker=1)\n        self.cellc_funcs = CpuCellcFuncs()\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/abstract-pipeline.html#cellcounter.pipeline.abstract_pipeline.AbstractPipeline.update_config","title":"<code>update_config(updates)</code>","text":"<p>Update project configuration with new values.</p> <p>Parameters:</p> Name Type Description Default <code>updates</code> <code>dict</code> <p>Key-value pairs to update in config.</p> required Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/abstract_pipeline.py</code> <pre><code>def update_config(self, updates: dict) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Update project configuration with new values.\n\n    Args:\n        updates: Key-value pairs to update in config.\n    \"\"\"\n    ProjConfig.ensure(self._pfm.config_fp, updates)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/config.html","title":"Configuration API","text":""},{"location":"reference/config.html#cellcounter.models.proj_config.ProjConfig","title":"<code>cellcounter.models.proj_config.ProjConfig</code>","text":"<p>               Bases: <code>BaseModel</code></p> <p>Pydantic model for pipeline configuration.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/models/proj_config/__init__.py</code> <pre><code>class ProjConfig(BaseModel):\n    \"\"\"Pydantic model for pipeline configuration.\"\"\"\n\n    model_config = ConfigDict(\n        extra=\"ignore\",\n        validate_default=True,\n        use_enum_values=True,\n    )\n\n    # Zarr storage\n    chunks: DimsConfig[PositiveInt] = DimsConfig.from_tuple(500, 500, 500)\n\n    # Tuning crop (subset for parameter exploration)\n    tuning_trim: DimsSliceConfig = DimsSliceConfig(\n        z=SliceConfig(start=0, stop=100, step=None),\n        y=SliceConfig(start=0, stop=2000, step=None),\n        x=SliceConfig(start=0, stop=2000, step=None),\n    )\n\n    # Nested configs\n    cluster: ClusterConfig = ClusterConfig()\n    reference: ReferenceConfig = ReferenceConfig()\n    registration: RegistrationConfig = RegistrationConfig()\n    cell_counting: CellCountingConfig = CellCountingConfig()\n    visual_check: VisualCheckConfig = VisualCheckConfig()\n\n    def update(self, **kwargs) -&gt; Self:\n        \"\"\"Update configs and return new instance.\"\"\"\n        return self.model_validate(self.model_copy(update=kwargs))\n\n    @classmethod\n    def read_file(cls, fp: Path | str) -&gt; Self:\n        \"\"\"Read configs from JSON file.\"\"\"\n        fp = Path(fp)\n        with fp.open(mode=\"r\") as f:\n            content = json.load(f)\n        return cls.model_validate(content)\n\n    def write_file(self, fp: Path | str) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Write configs to JSON file.\"\"\"\n        fp = Path(fp)\n        fp.parent.mkdir(exist_ok=True)\n        with fp.open(mode=\"w\") as f:\n            f.write(self.model_dump_json(indent=2))\n\n    @classmethod\n    def ensure(cls, config_fp: Path | str, updates: dict) -&gt; Self:\n        \"\"\"Load config from file, creating default if needed, and apply updates.\n\n        Args:\n            config_fp: Path to config file.\n            updates: Fields to update in the config.\n\n        Returns:\n            The loaded or created config.\n        \"\"\"\n        config_fp = Path(config_fp)\n        # Load existing config or create default if file doesn't exist\n        try:\n            config = cls.read_file(config_fp)\n        except FileNotFoundError:\n            config = cls()\n            config.write_file(config_fp)\n        # Update the config with any provided updates and pydantic validate\n        # Write back to file if updates to ensure the file is always in sync\n        if updates:\n            config = config.model_validate(config.model_copy(update=updates))\n            config.write_file(config_fp)\n        return config\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/config.html#cellcounter.models.proj_config.ProjConfig.ensure","title":"<code>ensure(config_fp, updates)</code>  <code>classmethod</code>","text":"<p>Load config from file, creating default if needed, and apply updates.</p> <p>Parameters:</p> Name Type Description Default <code>config_fp</code> <code>Path | str</code> <p>Path to config file.</p> required <code>updates</code> <code>dict</code> <p>Fields to update in the config.</p> required <p>Returns:</p> Type Description <code>Self</code> <p>The loaded or created config.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/models/proj_config/__init__.py</code> <pre><code>@classmethod\ndef ensure(cls, config_fp: Path | str, updates: dict) -&gt; Self:\n    \"\"\"Load config from file, creating default if needed, and apply updates.\n\n    Args:\n        config_fp: Path to config file.\n        updates: Fields to update in the config.\n\n    Returns:\n        The loaded or created config.\n    \"\"\"\n    config_fp = Path(config_fp)\n    # Load existing config or create default if file doesn't exist\n    try:\n        config = cls.read_file(config_fp)\n    except FileNotFoundError:\n        config = cls()\n        config.write_file(config_fp)\n    # Update the config with any provided updates and pydantic validate\n    # Write back to file if updates to ensure the file is always in sync\n    if updates:\n        config = config.model_validate(config.model_copy(update=updates))\n        config.write_file(config_fp)\n    return config\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/config.html#cellcounter.models.proj_config.ProjConfig.read_file","title":"<code>read_file(fp)</code>  <code>classmethod</code>","text":"<p>Read configs from JSON file.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/models/proj_config/__init__.py</code> <pre><code>@classmethod\ndef read_file(cls, fp: Path | str) -&gt; Self:\n    \"\"\"Read configs from JSON file.\"\"\"\n    fp = Path(fp)\n    with fp.open(mode=\"r\") as f:\n        content = json.load(f)\n    return cls.model_validate(content)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/config.html#cellcounter.models.proj_config.ProjConfig.update","title":"<code>update(**kwargs)</code>","text":"<p>Update configs and return new instance.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/models/proj_config/__init__.py</code> <pre><code>def update(self, **kwargs) -&gt; Self:\n    \"\"\"Update configs and return new instance.\"\"\"\n    return self.model_validate(self.model_copy(update=kwargs))\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/config.html#cellcounter.models.proj_config.ProjConfig.write_file","title":"<code>write_file(fp)</code>","text":"<p>Write configs to JSON file.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/models/proj_config/__init__.py</code> <pre><code>def write_file(self, fp: Path | str) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Write configs to JSON file.\"\"\"\n    fp = Path(fp)\n    fp.parent.mkdir(exist_ok=True)\n    with fp.open(mode=\"w\") as f:\n        f.write(self.model_dump_json(indent=2))\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html","title":"Pipeline API","text":"<p>Complete API reference for the <code>Pipeline</code> class.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#pipeline","title":"Pipeline","text":"<p><code>cellcounter.pipeline.pipeline.Pipeline</code></p> <p>The main orchestrator for cell counting workflows.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#constructor","title":"Constructor","text":"<pre><code>Pipeline(proj_dir: str | Path, *, tuning: bool = False)\n</code></pre> <p>Parameters:</p> Parameter Type Description <code>proj_dir</code> <code>str</code> | <code>Path</code> Path to project directory <code>tuning</code> <code>bool</code> If True, use tuning subdirectory <p>Example:</p> <pre><code>from cellcounter import Pipeline\n\n# Main pipeline\npipeline = Pipeline(\"/path/to/project\")\n\n# Tuning pipeline (processes crop only)\npipeline_tuning = Pipeline(\"/path/to/project\", tuning=True)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#properties","title":"Properties","text":""},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#config","title":"<code>config</code>","text":"<pre><code>@property\ndef config(self) -&gt; ProjConfig\n</code></pre> <p>Access project configuration.</p> <p>Returns: <code>ProjConfig</code> \u2014 Pydantic model with all settings</p> <p>Example:</p> <pre><code>print(pipeline.config.cell_counting.threshd_value)  # 60\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#pfm","title":"<code>pfm</code>","text":"<pre><code>@property\ndef pfm(self) -&gt; ProjFp\n</code></pre> <p>Access project filepath model.</p> <p>Returns: <code>ProjFp</code> \u2014 All file paths in the project</p> <p>Example:</p> <pre><code>print(pipeline.pfm.cells_agg_csv)\n# /path/to/project/cellcount/cells_agg.csv\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#tuning","title":"<code>tuning</code>","text":"<pre><code>@property\ndef tuning(self) -&gt; bool\n</code></pre> <p>Whether this is a tuning instance.</p> <p>Returns: <code>bool</code></p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#configuration-methods","title":"Configuration Methods","text":""},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#update_config","title":"<code>update_config</code>","text":"<pre><code>def update_config(self, updates) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Update project configuration and save to disk.</p> <p>Parameters:</p> Parameter Type Description <code>updates</code> Any Key-value pairs to update <p>Example:</p> <pre><code>pipeline.update_config(\n    cell_counting={\"threshd_value\": 45},\n    registration={\"ref_orientation\": {\"z\": -2, \"y\": 3, \"x\": 1}},\n)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#set_gpu","title":"<code>set_gpu</code>","text":"<pre><code>def set_gpu(self, *, enabled: bool = True) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Switch between GPU and CPU mode.</p> <p>Parameters:</p> Parameter Type Default Description <code>enabled</code> <code>bool</code> <code>True</code> Use GPU if True, CPU if False <p>Example:</p> <pre><code>pipeline.set_gpu(enabled=True)   # Use CuPy\npipeline.set_gpu(enabled=False)  # Use NumPy\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#inputoutput-methods","title":"Input/Output Methods","text":""},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#tiff2zarr","title":"<code>tiff2zarr</code>","text":"<pre><code>def tiff2zarr(self, in_fp: str | Path, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Convert TIFF file(s) to chunked Zarr format.</p> <p>Parameters:</p> Parameter Type Description <code>in_fp</code> <code>str</code> | <code>Path</code> Path to TIFF file or directory of TIFFs <code>overwrite</code> <code>bool</code> Overwrite existing output <p>Example:</p> <pre><code># Single multi-page TIFF\npipeline.tiff2zarr(\"/path/to/brain.tiff\")\n\n# Directory of single-plane TIFFs\npipeline.tiff2zarr(\"/path/to/tiff_folder/\")\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#rechunk_raw","title":"<code>rechunk_raw</code>","text":"<pre><code>def rechunk_raw(self) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Rechunk raw Zarr array to configured chunk size.</p> <p>Useful if chunk size needs adjustment after initial conversion.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#clean_proj","title":"<code>clean_proj</code>","text":"<pre><code>def clean_proj(self) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Remove all cellcount subdirectories.</p> <p>Warning: Destructive operation. Deletes all processing outputs.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#registration-pipeline","title":"Registration Pipeline","text":""},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#reg_ref_prepare","title":"<code>reg_ref_prepare</code>","text":"<pre><code>def reg_ref_prepare(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Prepare reference atlas images for registration.</p> <p>Copies and preprocesses reference/annotation images from atlas, applying orientation and trimming.</p> <p>Output files:</p> File Description <code>ref.tiff</code> Reference brain image <code>annot.tiff</code> Annotation volume <code>map.csv</code> Region hierarchy mapping <code>affine.txt</code> Affine transformation parameters <code>bspline.txt</code> B-spline transformation parameters"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#reg_img_rough","title":"<code>reg_img_rough</code>","text":"<pre><code>def reg_img_rough(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Rough downsampling by integer strides.</p> <p>First pass downsampling for registration pyramid.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#reg_img_fine","title":"<code>reg_img_fine</code>","text":"<pre><code>def reg_img_fine(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Fine downsampling using Gaussian zoom.</p> <p>Second pass downsampling for registration pyramid.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#reg_img_trim","title":"<code>reg_img_trim</code>","text":"<pre><code>def reg_img_trim(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Trim downsampled image to region of interest.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#reg_img_bound","title":"<code>reg_img_bound</code>","text":"<pre><code>def reg_img_bound(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Apply intensity bounds to trimmed image.</p> <p>Clips intensities for better registration contrast.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#reg_elastix","title":"<code>reg_elastix</code>","text":"<pre><code>def reg_elastix(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Register image to atlas using elastix.</p> <p>Performs non-rigid registration to align image to reference atlas.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#make_tuning_arr","title":"<code>make_tuning_arr</code>","text":"<pre><code>def make_tuning_arr(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Crop raw Zarr to create tuning subset.</p> <p>Creates a smaller Zarr for fast parameter tuning.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#cell-counting-pipeline","title":"Cell Counting Pipeline","text":""},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#tophat_filter","title":"<code>tophat_filter</code>","text":"<pre><code>def tophat_filter(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 1: Top-hat filter for background removal.</p> <p>Uses morphological opening to remove large-scale illumination variations.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#dog_filter","title":"<code>dog_filter</code>","text":"<pre><code>def dog_filter(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 2: Difference of Gaussians for edge enhancement.</p> <p>Enhances cell boundaries while suppressing slow intensity variations.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#adaptive_threshold_prep","title":"<code>adaptive_threshold_prep</code>","text":"<pre><code>def adaptive_threshold_prep(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 3: Gaussian subtraction for adaptive thresholding.</p> <p>Subtracts large-scale Gaussian to normalize local contrast.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#threshold","title":"<code>threshold</code>","text":"<pre><code>def threshold(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 4: Manual intensity thresholding.</p> <p>Creates binary mask based on <code>threshd_value</code> parameter.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#label_thresholded","title":"<code>label_thresholded</code>","text":"<pre><code>def label_thresholded(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 5: Label contiguous regions in thresholded image.</p> <p>Assigns unique labels to connected foreground components.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#compute_thresholded_volumes","title":"<code>compute_thresholded_volumes</code>","text":"<pre><code>def compute_thresholded_volumes(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 6: Compute connected component volumes.</p> <p>Uses union-find to merge labels across chunk boundaries.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#filter_thresholded","title":"<code>filter_thresholded</code>","text":"<pre><code>def filter_thresholded(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 7: Filter thresholded objects by size.</p> <p>Removes objects outside size range (<code>min_threshd_size</code>, <code>max_threshd_size</code>).</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#detect_maxima","title":"<code>detect_maxima</code>","text":"<pre><code>def detect_maxima(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 8: Detect local maxima as cell candidates.</p> <p>Finds intensity peaks within radius <code>maxima_radius</code>.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#label_maxima","title":"<code>label_maxima</code>","text":"<pre><code>def label_maxima(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 9: Label maxima points.</p> <p>Assigns unique labels to each detected maximum.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#watershed","title":"<code>watershed</code>","text":"<pre><code>def watershed(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 10: Watershed segmentation.</p> <p>Separates touching cells using watershed algorithm on maxima labels.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#compute_watershed_volumes","title":"<code>compute_watershed_volumes</code>","text":"<pre><code>def compute_watershed_volumes(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Compute watershed cell volumes.</p> <p>Uses union-find for cross-chunk volume computation.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#filter_watershed","title":"<code>filter_watershed</code>","text":"<pre><code>def filter_watershed(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 12: Filter watershed objects by size.</p> <p>Final size filtering using <code>min_wshed_size</code> and <code>max_wshed_size</code>.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#save_cells_table","title":"<code>save_cells_table</code>","text":"<pre><code>def save_cells_table(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Step 13: Extract and save cells table.</p> <p>Extracts cell measurements (coordinates, volume, intensity) and saves to Parquet.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#mapping-pipeline","title":"Mapping Pipeline","text":""},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#transform_coords","title":"<code>transform_coords</code>","text":"<pre><code>def transform_coords(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Transform cell coordinates to reference atlas space.</p> <p>Applies registration transformation to raw coordinates.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#cell_mapping","title":"<code>cell_mapping</code>","text":"<pre><code>def cell_mapping(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Map transformed cell coordinates to region IDs.</p> <p>Assigns each cell to an anatomical brain region using annotation volume.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#group_cells","title":"<code>group_cells</code>","text":"<pre><code>def group_cells(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Group cells by region and aggregate statistics.</p> <p>Aggregates cell counts, volumes, and intensities per brain region.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#cells2csv","title":"<code>cells2csv</code>","text":"<pre><code>def cells2csv(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Save aggregated cell data to CSV.</p> <p>Exports final results in a readable table format.</p>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#orchestration-methods","title":"Orchestration Methods","text":""},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#run_pipeline","title":"<code>run_pipeline</code>","text":"<pre><code>def run_pipeline(\n    self,\n    in_fp: str,\n    *,\n    steps: list[str] | None = None,\n    overwrite: bool = False\n) -&gt; None\n</code></pre> <p>Run pipeline steps in order.</p> <p>Parameters:</p> Parameter Type Description <code>in_fp</code> <code>str</code> Input file path for <code>tiff2zarr</code> <code>steps</code> <code>list[str]</code> Optional: specific steps to run <code>overwrite</code> <code>bool</code> Overwrite existing outputs <p>Example:</p> <pre><code># Run full pipeline\npipeline.run_pipeline(\"/path/to/image.tiff\")\n\n# Run only specific steps\npipeline.run_pipeline(\n    \"/path/to/image.tiff\",\n    steps=[\"tiff2zarr\", \"tophat_filter\", \"dog_filter\"]\n)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#class-methods","title":"Class Methods","text":""},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#get_imgs_ls","title":"<code>get_imgs_ls</code>","text":"<pre><code>@staticmethod\ndef get_imgs_ls(imgs_dir: Path | str) -&gt; list[Path]\n</code></pre> <p>Get sorted list of subdirectories in a directory.</p> <p>Useful for batch processing multiple images.</p> <p>Parameters:</p> Parameter Type Description <code>imgs_dir</code> <code>str</code> | <code>Path</code> Directory containing image folders <p>Returns: <code>list[Path]</code> \u2014 Naturally sorted subdirectory paths</p> <p>Example:</p> <pre><code>imgs = Pipeline.get_imgs_ls(\"/path/to/stitched_imgs\")\n# Returns: [Path(\"mouse_01\"), Path(\"mouse_02\"), ...]\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#step-registries","title":"Step Registries","text":"<p>Class attributes listing available pipeline steps:</p> <pre><code># Registration steps (7 total)\nPipeline.STEPS_REGISTRATION = (\n    \"tiff2zarr\",       # Convert to Zarr\n    \"reg_ref_prepare\", # Prepare reference\n    \"reg_img_rough\",   # Rough downsample\n    \"reg_img_fine\",    # Fine downsample\n    \"reg_img_trim\",    # Trim to ROI\n    \"reg_img_bound\",   # Intensity bounds\n    \"reg_elastix\",     # Register\n)\n\n# Cell counting steps (13 total)\nPipeline.STEPS_CELL_COUNTING = (\n    \"tophat_filter\",\n    \"dog_filter\",\n    \"adaptive_threshold_prep\",\n    \"threshold\",\n    \"label_thresholded\",\n    \"compute_thresholded_volumes\",\n    \"filter_thresholded\",\n    \"detect_maxima\",\n    \"label_maxima\",\n    \"watershed\",\n    \"compute_watershed_volumes\",\n    \"filter_watershed\",\n    \"save_cells_table\",\n)\n\n# Mapping steps (4 total)\nPipeline.STEPS_MAPPING = (\n    \"transform_coords\",\n    \"cell_mapping\",\n    \"group_cells\",\n    \"cells2csv\",\n)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/pipeline.html#full-example","title":"Full Example","text":"<pre><code>from cellcounter import Pipeline\n\n# Initialize\npipeline = Pipeline(\"/path/to/project\")\n\n# Configure\npipeline.update_config(\n    registration={\n        \"ref_orientation\": {\"z\": -2, \"y\": 3, \"x\": 1},\n        \"downsample_rough\": {\"z\": 3, \"y\": 6, \"x\": 6},\n    },\n    cell_counting={\n        \"threshd_value\": 60,\n        \"min_wshed_size\": 1,\n        \"max_wshed_size\": 700,\n    },\n)\n\n# Run everything\npipeline.run_pipeline(\"/path/to/image.tiff\")\n\n# Or step by step with custom logic\npipeline.tiff2zarr(\"/path/to/image.tiff\")\npipeline.reg_ref_prepare()\n# ... custom processing ...\npipeline.cells2csv()\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/visual-check.html","title":"Visual Check API","text":""},{"location":"reference/visual-check.html#cellcounter.pipeline.visual_check.VisualCheck","title":"<code>cellcounter.pipeline.visual_check.VisualCheck</code>","text":"<p>               Bases: <code>AbstractPipeline</code></p> <p>Visual quality control for pipeline outputs.</p> <p>Generates visualization arrays (points, heatmaps, combined images) for verifying registration and cell counting results in Napari.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/visual_check.py</code> <pre><code>class VisualCheck(AbstractPipeline):\n    \"\"\"Visual quality control for pipeline outputs.\n\n    Generates visualization arrays (points, heatmaps, combined images)\n    for verifying registration and cell counting results in Napari.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    STEPS_VISUAL_CHECK = (\n        \"combine_reg\",\n        \"coords2points_raw\",\n        \"combine_cellc\",\n        \"coords2points_trfm\",\n        \"coords2heatmap_trfm\",\n        \"combine_heatmap_trfm\",\n    )\n\n    @_check_overwrite(\"points_raw\")\n    def coords2points_raw(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Generate single-voxel markers at raw cell coordinates.\"\"\"\n        with cluster_process(self.busy_cluster()):\n            visual_check_funcs_dask.coords2points(\n                coords=pd.read_parquet(self.pfm.cells_raw_df),\n                shape=da.from_zarr(self.pfm.raw).shape,\n                out_fp=self.pfm.points_raw,\n                chunks=self.pfm.config.chunks.to_tuple(),\n            )\n\n    @_check_overwrite(\"heatmap_raw\")\n    def coords2heatmap_raw(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Generate spherical heatmap at raw cell coordinates.\"\"\"\n        with cluster_process(self.busy_cluster()):\n            visual_check_funcs_dask.coords2heatmap(\n                coords=pd.read_parquet(self.pfm.cells_raw_df),\n                shape=da.from_zarr(self.pfm.raw).shape,\n                out_fp=self.pfm.heatmap_raw,\n                radius=self.config.visual_check.heatmap_raw_radius,\n                chunks=self.pfm.config.chunks.to_tuple(),\n            )\n\n    @_check_overwrite(\"points_trfm\")\n    def coords2points_trfm(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Generate single-voxel markers at transformed cell coordinates.\"\"\"\n        visual_check_funcs_tiff.coords2points(\n            coords=pd.read_parquet(self.pfm.cells_trfm_df),\n            shape=tifffile.imread(self.pfm.ref).shape,\n            out_fp=self.pfm.points_trfm,\n        )\n\n    @_check_overwrite(\"heatmap_trfm\")\n    def coords2heatmap_trfm(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Generate spherical heatmap at transformed cell coordinates.\"\"\"\n        visual_check_funcs_tiff.coords2heatmap(\n            coords=pd.read_parquet(self.pfm.cells_trfm_df),\n            shape=tifffile.imread(self.pfm.ref).shape,\n            out_fp=self.pfm.heatmap_trfm,\n            radius=self.config.visual_check.heatmap_trfm_radius,\n        )\n\n    @_check_overwrite(\"comb_reg\")\n    def combine_reg(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Combine registration images into multi-channel TIFF for viewing.\"\"\"\n        combine_arrs(\n            fp_in_ls=(self.pfm.trimmed, self.pfm.bounded, self.pfm.regresult),\n            fp_out=self.pfm.comb_reg,\n        )\n\n    @_check_overwrite(\"comb_cellc\")\n    def combine_cellc(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Combine cell counting images into multi-channel TIFF for viewing.\n\n        If not tuning (i.e. is prod), then we have to trim anyway\n        - otherwise image is too large.\n        \"\"\"\n        z_trim = slice(None)\n        y_trim = slice(None)\n        x_trim = slice(None)\n        if not self.tuning:\n            z_trim = self.config.visual_check.cellcount_trim.z.to_slice()\n            y_trim = self.config.visual_check.cellcount_trim.y.to_slice()\n            x_trim = self.config.visual_check.cellcount_trim.x.to_slice()\n        combine_arrs(\n            fp_in_ls=(self.pfm.raw, self.pfm.threshd_filt, self.pfm.wshed_filt),\n            fp_out=self.pfm.comb_cellc,\n            trimmer=(z_trim, y_trim, x_trim),\n        )\n\n    @_check_overwrite(\"comb_heatmap\")\n    def combine_heatmap_trfm(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Combine heatmap image into multi-channel TIFF for viewing.\"\"\"\n        combine_arrs(\n            fp_in_ls=(self.pfm.ref, self.pfm.annot, self.pfm.heatmap_trfm),\n            fp_out=self.pfm.comb_heatmap,\n        )\n\n    #############################################\n    # RUN PIPELINE\n    #############################################\n\n    def run_visual_check_steps(\n        self,\n        *,\n        steps: list[str] | None = None,\n        overwrite: bool = False,\n    ) -&gt; None:\n        \"\"\"Running all visual check pipelines in order.\"\"\"\n        steps = steps or [*self.STEPS_VISUAL_CHECK]\n        for step in steps:\n            getattr(self, step)(overwrite=overwrite)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/visual-check.html#cellcounter.pipeline.visual_check.VisualCheck.combine_cellc","title":"<code>combine_cellc(*, overwrite=False)</code>","text":"<p>Combine cell counting images into multi-channel TIFF for viewing.</p> <p>If not tuning (i.e. is prod), then we have to trim anyway - otherwise image is too large.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/visual_check.py</code> <pre><code>@_check_overwrite(\"comb_cellc\")\ndef combine_cellc(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Combine cell counting images into multi-channel TIFF for viewing.\n\n    If not tuning (i.e. is prod), then we have to trim anyway\n    - otherwise image is too large.\n    \"\"\"\n    z_trim = slice(None)\n    y_trim = slice(None)\n    x_trim = slice(None)\n    if not self.tuning:\n        z_trim = self.config.visual_check.cellcount_trim.z.to_slice()\n        y_trim = self.config.visual_check.cellcount_trim.y.to_slice()\n        x_trim = self.config.visual_check.cellcount_trim.x.to_slice()\n    combine_arrs(\n        fp_in_ls=(self.pfm.raw, self.pfm.threshd_filt, self.pfm.wshed_filt),\n        fp_out=self.pfm.comb_cellc,\n        trimmer=(z_trim, y_trim, x_trim),\n    )\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/visual-check.html#cellcounter.pipeline.visual_check.VisualCheck.combine_heatmap_trfm","title":"<code>combine_heatmap_trfm(*, overwrite=False)</code>","text":"<p>Combine heatmap image into multi-channel TIFF for viewing.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/visual_check.py</code> <pre><code>@_check_overwrite(\"comb_heatmap\")\ndef combine_heatmap_trfm(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Combine heatmap image into multi-channel TIFF for viewing.\"\"\"\n    combine_arrs(\n        fp_in_ls=(self.pfm.ref, self.pfm.annot, self.pfm.heatmap_trfm),\n        fp_out=self.pfm.comb_heatmap,\n    )\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/visual-check.html#cellcounter.pipeline.visual_check.VisualCheck.combine_reg","title":"<code>combine_reg(*, overwrite=False)</code>","text":"<p>Combine registration images into multi-channel TIFF for viewing.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/visual_check.py</code> <pre><code>@_check_overwrite(\"comb_reg\")\ndef combine_reg(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Combine registration images into multi-channel TIFF for viewing.\"\"\"\n    combine_arrs(\n        fp_in_ls=(self.pfm.trimmed, self.pfm.bounded, self.pfm.regresult),\n        fp_out=self.pfm.comb_reg,\n    )\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/visual-check.html#cellcounter.pipeline.visual_check.VisualCheck.coords2heatmap_raw","title":"<code>coords2heatmap_raw(*, overwrite=False)</code>","text":"<p>Generate spherical heatmap at raw cell coordinates.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/visual_check.py</code> <pre><code>@_check_overwrite(\"heatmap_raw\")\ndef coords2heatmap_raw(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Generate spherical heatmap at raw cell coordinates.\"\"\"\n    with cluster_process(self.busy_cluster()):\n        visual_check_funcs_dask.coords2heatmap(\n            coords=pd.read_parquet(self.pfm.cells_raw_df),\n            shape=da.from_zarr(self.pfm.raw).shape,\n            out_fp=self.pfm.heatmap_raw,\n            radius=self.config.visual_check.heatmap_raw_radius,\n            chunks=self.pfm.config.chunks.to_tuple(),\n        )\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/visual-check.html#cellcounter.pipeline.visual_check.VisualCheck.coords2heatmap_trfm","title":"<code>coords2heatmap_trfm(*, overwrite=False)</code>","text":"<p>Generate spherical heatmap at transformed cell coordinates.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/visual_check.py</code> <pre><code>@_check_overwrite(\"heatmap_trfm\")\ndef coords2heatmap_trfm(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Generate spherical heatmap at transformed cell coordinates.\"\"\"\n    visual_check_funcs_tiff.coords2heatmap(\n        coords=pd.read_parquet(self.pfm.cells_trfm_df),\n        shape=tifffile.imread(self.pfm.ref).shape,\n        out_fp=self.pfm.heatmap_trfm,\n        radius=self.config.visual_check.heatmap_trfm_radius,\n    )\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/visual-check.html#cellcounter.pipeline.visual_check.VisualCheck.coords2points_raw","title":"<code>coords2points_raw(*, overwrite=False)</code>","text":"<p>Generate single-voxel markers at raw cell coordinates.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/visual_check.py</code> <pre><code>@_check_overwrite(\"points_raw\")\ndef coords2points_raw(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Generate single-voxel markers at raw cell coordinates.\"\"\"\n    with cluster_process(self.busy_cluster()):\n        visual_check_funcs_dask.coords2points(\n            coords=pd.read_parquet(self.pfm.cells_raw_df),\n            shape=da.from_zarr(self.pfm.raw).shape,\n            out_fp=self.pfm.points_raw,\n            chunks=self.pfm.config.chunks.to_tuple(),\n        )\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/visual-check.html#cellcounter.pipeline.visual_check.VisualCheck.coords2points_trfm","title":"<code>coords2points_trfm(*, overwrite=False)</code>","text":"<p>Generate single-voxel markers at transformed cell coordinates.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/visual_check.py</code> <pre><code>@_check_overwrite(\"points_trfm\")\ndef coords2points_trfm(self, *, overwrite: bool = False) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Generate single-voxel markers at transformed cell coordinates.\"\"\"\n    visual_check_funcs_tiff.coords2points(\n        coords=pd.read_parquet(self.pfm.cells_trfm_df),\n        shape=tifffile.imread(self.pfm.ref).shape,\n        out_fp=self.pfm.points_trfm,\n    )\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"reference/visual-check.html#cellcounter.pipeline.visual_check.VisualCheck.run_visual_check_steps","title":"<code>run_visual_check_steps(*, steps=None, overwrite=False)</code>","text":"<p>Running all visual check pipelines in order.</p> Source code in <code>cellcounter/pipeline/visual_check.py</code> <pre><code>def run_visual_check_steps(\n    self,\n    *,\n    steps: list[str] | None = None,\n    overwrite: bool = False,\n) -&gt; None:\n    \"\"\"Running all visual check pipelines in order.\"\"\"\n    steps = steps or [*self.STEPS_VISUAL_CHECK]\n    for step in steps:\n        getattr(self, step)(overwrite=overwrite)\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html","title":"Installation","text":"<p>This guide walks you through installing CellCounter from scratch. Choose the path that matches your setup.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#what-youll-need","title":"What You'll Need","text":"<p>Before starting, ensure you have:</p> <ul> <li> A computer running Ubuntu 24.04 LTS (other Linux distributions may work but are untested)</li> <li> Python 3.12 (this exact version is required)</li> <li> At least 50GB free disk space (for atlas + sample data)</li> <li> (Recommended) An NVIDIA GPU with 8GB+ VRAM for processing large images</li> </ul>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#platform-specific-setup","title":"Platform-Specific Setup","text":"With GPU (Recommended)CPU Only <p>If you have an NVIDIA GPU, you'll be able to process whole-brain images (~90GB) efficiently.</p> <p>CellCounter can run without a GPU, but processing large images may be slow or run out of memory.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#step-1-install-build-tools","title":"Step 1: Install Build Tools","text":"<pre><code>sudo apt update\nsudo apt install build-essential python3-dev gcc g++\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#step-2-install-nvidia-drivers","title":"Step 2: Install NVIDIA Drivers","text":"<pre><code># Check available drivers\nsudo ubuntu-drivers list\n\n# Install the recommended driver (replace with your recommended version)\nsudo ubuntu-drivers install nvidia-driver-590-open\n\n# Reboot and verify\nsudo reboot\nnvidia-smi\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#step-3-install-cuda-toolkit","title":"Step 3: Install CUDA Toolkit","text":"<p>Download from NVIDIA CUDA Downloads:</p> <ul> <li>Operating System: Linux</li> <li>Architecture: x86_64</li> <li>Distribution: Ubuntu</li> <li>Version: 24.04</li> <li>Installer Type: deb (local)</li> </ul> <p>Follow the provided installation commands, then verify:</p> <pre><code>nvcc --version\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#step-1-install-build-tools_1","title":"Step 1: Install Build Tools","text":"<pre><code>sudo apt update\nsudo apt install build-essential python3-dev gcc g++\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#step-2-verify-installation","title":"Step 2: Verify Installation","text":"<pre><code>python3 --version  # Should show 3.12.x\n</code></pre> <p>Performance Warning</p> <p>CPU-only mode is suitable for small test images (&lt;10GB). For whole-brain images (~90GB), a GPU is strongly recommended.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#install-cellcounter","title":"Install CellCounter","text":""},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#step-1-install-uv-python-package-manager","title":"Step 1: Install uv (Python Package Manager)","text":"<p>uv is a fast, modern Python package manager.</p> <pre><code># Install uv\ncurl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh\n\n# Verify installation\nuv --version\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#step-2-clone-and-install","title":"Step 2: Clone and Install","text":"<pre><code># Clone the repository\ngit clone https://github.com/tlee08/cellcounter.git\ncd cellcounter\n\n# Install dependencies\nuv sync\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#step-3-install-gpu-support-gpu-users-only","title":"Step 3: Install GPU Support (GPU users only)","text":"<pre><code>uv sync --extra gpu\n</code></pre> <p>This installs CuPy and Dask-CUDA for GPU acceleration.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#download-reference-atlas","title":"Download Reference Atlas","text":"<p>CellCounter needs the Allen Mouse Brain Atlas for registration. Download it with:</p> <pre><code>uv run cellcounter-init\n</code></pre> <p>This will: - Download the reference brain atlas (~1GB) - Download the annotation volume (~1GB) - Download the region hierarchy mapping (~100MB) - Place them in <code>~/.cellcounter/atlas/</code></p> <p>The download may take 5-10 minutes depending on your connection.</p> <p>Atlas Location</p> <p>The atlas is saved in your home directory under <code>~/.cellcounter/atlas/</code>. You only need to do this once \u2014 all projects will share this atlas.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#verify-installation","title":"Verify Installation","text":"<p>Test that everything is working:</p> <pre><code># Test Python imports\nuv run python -c \"from cellcounter import Pipeline; print('\u2713 CellCounter installed successfully')\"\n\n# Test GPU (if applicable)\nuv run python -c \"import cupy; print('\u2713 GPU (CuPy) available')\"\n</code></pre> <p>Expected output: <pre><code>\u2713 CellCounter installed successfully\n\u2713 GPU (CuPy) available  # (GPU users only)\n</code></pre></p>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#common-installation-issues","title":"Common Installation Issues","text":""},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#issue-python3-dev-not-found","title":"Issue: \"python3-dev not found\"","text":"<p>Solution: Install the Python development headers:</p> <pre><code>sudo apt install python3.12-dev\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#issue-cuda-not-found-gpu-users","title":"Issue: \"CUDA not found\" (GPU users)","text":"<p>Solution: Check that CUDA is in your PATH:</p> <pre><code># Add to ~/.bashrc if needed\nexport PATH=/usr/local/cuda/bin:$PATH\nexport LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/usr/local/cuda/lib64:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH\n</code></pre> <p>Then reload:</p> <pre><code>source ~/.bashrc\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#issue-no-module-named-cellcounter","title":"Issue: \"No module named cellcounter\"","text":"<p>Solution: Make sure you're running commands from the cellcounter directory:</p> <pre><code>cd /path/to/cellcounter\nuv sync\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/installation.html#next-steps","title":"Next Steps","text":"<p>Now that CellCounter is installed, proceed to the Quick Start tutorial to process your first image.</p> <p>Or, if you have multiple images to process, see Batch Processing.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html","title":"Quick Start Tutorial","text":"<p>Process your first microscopy image from TIFF file to cell counts by brain region.</p> <p>Prerequisites</p> <p>Make sure you've completed the Installation guide first.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#what-well-do","title":"What We'll Do","text":"<p>By the end of this tutorial, you will:</p> <ol> <li>Create a new project with the correct folder structure</li> <li>Configure parameters for your specific image</li> <li>Run image registration (align to brain atlas)</li> <li>Tune cell detection parameters on a small crop</li> <li>Run cell detection on the full image</li> <li>Map cells to brain regions</li> <li>Export results to CSV</li> </ol>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#overview","title":"Overview","text":"<p>The pipeline has three main stages:</p> <pre><code>flowchart LR\n    A[TIFF Images] --&gt; B[Registration]\n    A --&gt; C[Cell Detection]\n    C --&gt; D[Region Mapping]\n    B --&gt; D\n    D --&gt; E[Results CSV]\n\n    style A fill:#e1f5fe\n    style E fill:#c8e6c9</code></pre> Stage What It Does Time (GPU) Registration Converts TIFF, aligns image to Allen Atlas 30-60 min Cell Detection Finds cFos+ cells using watershed segmentation 20-40 min Region Mapping Assigns each cell to a brain region 5-10 min"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#step-1-create-a-project","title":"Step 1: Create a Project","text":"<p>Projects keep your data organized and store all processing parameters.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#choose-your-workspace","title":"Choose Your Workspace","text":"<p>Create a folder for your analysis. We'll use two folders:</p> <pre><code># Folder containing your TIFF images\nmkdir -p /path/to/your/data\n\n# Folder where results will be saved\nmkdir -p /path/to/your/analysis\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#create-the-project","title":"Create the Project","text":"<pre><code>cd /path/to/your/analysis\nuv run cellcounter-make-project\n</code></pre> <p>You'll see: <pre><code>? Enter project name:  my_experiment\n\u2713 Created project: my_experiment\n</code></pre></p> <p>This creates:</p> <pre><code>my_experiment/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 config.json          # \u2190 All parameters (we'll edit this)\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 cellcount/           # \u2190 Where outputs will be saved\n    \u251c\u2500\u2500 raw.zarr/        # Converted image\n    \u251c\u2500\u2500 cells_agg.csv    # Final results\n    \u2514\u2500\u2500 ... (intermediate files)\n</code></pre> <p>Checkpoint</p> <p>You now have a project folder ready for processing.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#step-2-load-and-configure-your-project","title":"Step 2: Load and Configure Your Project","text":"<p>Start Python and load your project:</p> <pre><code>from cellcounter import Pipeline\n\n# Load the project\npipeline = Pipeline(\"/path/to/your/analysis/my_experiment\")\n\n# View current config\nprint(pipeline.config.cell_counting.threshd_value)  # Default: 60\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#understanding-your-image","title":"Understanding Your Image","text":"<p>Before configuring, you need to know:</p> <ol> <li>Image dimensions (z, y, x in voxels)</li> <li>Resolution (microns per voxel)</li> <li>Orientation (how axes map to atlas)</li> <li>Intensity range</li> </ol> <p>Use ImageJ/Fiji or this quick Python check:</p> <pre><code>import tifffile\nimg = tifffile.imread(\"/path/to/your/image.tiff\")\nprint(f\"Shape: {img.shape}\")  # (z, y, x)\nprint(f\"Dtype: {img.dtype}\")  # uint16, uint32, etc.\nprint(f\"Min/Max: {img.min()}, {img.max()}\")\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#update-configuration","title":"Update Configuration","text":"<p>The most important parameters to adjust:</p> <pre><code>pipeline.update_config(\n    # Image chunking (affects memory usage)\n    chunks={\"z\": 500, \"y\": 500, \"x\": 500},\n\n    # Orientation: map your image axes to atlas\n    # Use negative values to flip axes\n    registration={\n        \"ref_orientation\": {\"z\": -2, \"y\": 3, \"x\": 1},\n        # -2 means: flip axis 2 (z), use as z\n        #  3 means: use axis 3 (y) as y\n        #  1 means: use axis 1 (x) as x\n    },\n\n    # Downsampling: adjust for your resolution\n    # Whole-brain lightsheet often needs (3, 6, 6)\n    registration={\n        \"downsample_rough\": {\"z\": 3, \"y\": 6, \"x\": 6},\n        \"downsample_fine\": {\"z\": 1.0, \"y\": 0.6, \"x\": 0.6},\n    },\n\n    # Cell counting parameters\n    cell_counting={\n        # Detection sensitivity (lower = more cells detected)\n        \"threshd_value\": 60,\n\n        # Cell size range (in voxels)\n        \"min_wshed_size\": 1,    # Minimum cell size\n        \"max_wshed_size\": 700,  # Maximum cell size\n\n        # Background removal\n        \"tophat_radius\": 10,\n    },\n)\n</code></pre> <p>Finding the Right Orientation</p> <p>The Allen Atlas has axes (z=inferior-superior, y=anterior-posterior, x=left-right). Use napari to open your image and compare with the reference atlas to determine the correct mapping.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#step-3-convert-tiff-to-zarr","title":"Step 3: Convert TIFF to Zarr","text":"<p>CellCounter uses Zarr for efficient chunked storage.</p> <pre><code># Convert your TIFF\npipeline.tiff2zarr(\"/path/to/your/image.tiff\")\n</code></pre> <p>This creates <code>cellcount/raw.zarr/</code> with your image in chunked format.</p> <p>TIFF Variations</p> <p>CellCounter supports: - Single multi-page TIFF files - Directories of single-plane TIFFs (will be stacked by natural sort order)</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#step-4-run-registration","title":"Step 4: Run Registration","text":"<p>Registration aligns your image to the Allen Atlas. This step: 1. Prepares reference images 2. Downsamples your image to match atlas resolution 3. Runs elastix registration</p> <pre><code># Prepare reference (do once)\npipeline.reg_ref_prepare()\n\n# Downsample steps\npipeline.reg_img_rough()    # Integer stride downsample (~5 min)\npipeline.reg_img_fine()     # Gaussian zoom (~2 min)\npipeline.reg_img_trim()     # Trim to region (~1 min)\npipeline.reg_img_bound()    # Clip intensity (~1 min)\n\n# Register\npipeline.reg_elastix()      # Elastix registration (~20-30 min)\n</code></pre> <p>Checkpoint</p> <p>You now have a registered image aligned to the atlas. Verify with: <pre><code>from cellcounter import VisualCheck\n\nvc = VisualCheck(\"/path/to/your/analysis/my_experiment\")\nvc.combine_reg()  # Creates combined_reg.tiff for inspection\n</code></pre></p>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#step-5-tune-cell-detection","title":"Step 5: Tune Cell Detection","text":"<p>Don't run on full image yet! First, tune parameters on a small cropped region.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#create-tuning-crop","title":"Create Tuning Crop","text":"<pre><code># Define crop region for tuning (choose a representative region with cells)\npipeline.update_config(\n    tuning_trim={\n        \"z\": {\"start\": 700, \"stop\": 800, \"step\": None},   # 100 z-slices\n        \"y\": {\"start\": 1000, \"stop\": 3000, \"step\": None}, # 2000 y-pixels\n        \"x\": {\"start\": 1000, \"stop\": 3000, \"step\": None}, # 2000 x-pixels\n    }\n)\n\n# Create the tuning crop\npipeline.make_tuning_arr()\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#run-cell-counting-on-tuning-crop","title":"Run Cell Counting on Tuning Crop","text":"<pre><code># Use tuning=True to process only the crop\npipeline_tuning = Pipeline(\n    \"/path/to/your/analysis/my_experiment\",\n    tuning=True\n)\n\n# Run cell detection pipeline\npipeline_tuning.tophat_filter()              # Background removal\npipeline_tuning.dog_filter()                 # Edge enhancement\npipeline_tuning.adaptive_threshold_prep()    # Adaptive thresholding\npipeline_tuning.threshold()                  # Binary threshold\npipeline_tuning.label_thresholded()          # Label regions\npipeline_tuning.compute_thresholded_volumes() # Compute sizes\npipeline_tuning.filter_thresholded()         # Size filter #1\npipeline_tuning.detect_maxima()              # Find cell centers\npipeline_tuning.label_maxima()               # Label centers\npipeline_tuning.watershed()                  # Segment touching cells\npipeline_tuning.compute_watershed_volumes()  # Compute cell sizes\npipeline_tuning.filter_watershed()           # Size filter #2\n\n# Visualize results\nvc_tuning = VisualCheck(\n    \"/path/to/your/analysis/my_experiment\",\n    tuning=True\n)\nvc_tuning.combine_cellc()  # Creates combined file for inspection\n</code></pre> <p>Open <code>cellcount/tuning/combined_cellc.tiff</code> in napari to verify: - Are cells being detected? (blue channel = thresholded, green = final cells) - Are cells being split correctly? (watershed should separate touching cells) - Are debris/dust particles filtered out? (adjust size filters)</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#iterate-until-satisfied","title":"Iterate Until Satisfied","text":"<p>Adjust parameters and re-run tuning until detection looks good:</p> <pre><code># If too few cells detected, lower threshold\npipeline_tuning.update_config(cell_counting={\"threshd_value\": 50})\n\n# If too many small noise artifacts, increase min size\npipeline_tuning.update_config(cell_counting={\"min_wshed_size\": 10})\n\n# Re-run cell counting steps (overwrite=True to update)\npipeline_tuning.dog_filter(overwrite=True)\npipeline_tuning.threshold(overwrite=True)\n# ... etc\n</code></pre> <p>Checkpoint</p> <p>You now have cell detection parameters that work for your data.</p>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#step-6-run-full-cell-counting","title":"Step 6: Run Full Cell Counting","text":"<p>Now run with <code>tuning=False</code> on the full image:</p> <pre><code>pipeline_full = Pipeline(\n    \"/path/to/your/analysis/my_experiment\",\n    tuning=False\n)\n\n# Run same steps, now on full image (~20-40 min)\npipeline_full.tophat_filter()\npipeline_full.dog_filter()\npipeline_full.adaptive_threshold_prep()\npipeline_full.threshold()\npipeline_full.label_thresholded()\npipeline_full.compute_thresholded_volumes()\npipeline_full.filter_thresholded()\npipeline_full.detect_maxima()\npipeline_full.label_maxima()\npipeline_full.watershed()\npipeline_full.compute_watershed_volumes()\npipeline_full.filter_watershed()\n\n# Extract cell measurements\npipeline_full.save_cells_table()\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#step-7-map-cells-to-brain-regions","title":"Step 7: Map Cells to Brain Regions","text":"<pre><code># Transform coordinates to atlas space\npipeline_full.transform_coords()\n\n# Assign each cell to a brain region\npipeline_full.cell_mapping()\n\n# Group cells by region and aggregate\npipeline_full.group_cells()\n\n# Export to CSV\npipeline_full.cells2csv()\n</code></pre> <p>Done!</p> <p>Your results are in <code>cellcount/cells_agg.csv</code></p>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#understanding-your-results","title":"Understanding Your Results","text":"<p>Open <code>cellcount/cells_agg.csv</code>:</p> Column Description <code>id</code> Allen Atlas region ID <code>name</code> Brain region name <code>acronym</code> Short name (e.g., \"CA1\", \"MOp\") <code>cell_count</code> Number of cells in this region <code>volume</code> Total cell volume (voxels) <code>sum_intensity</code> Sum of fluorescence intensities <code>avg_intensity</code> Average intensity per cell <code>voxel_intensity</code> Intensity per voxel"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#quick-reference-common-issues","title":"Quick Reference: Common Issues","text":""},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#not-detecting-any-cells","title":"\"Not detecting any cells\"","text":"<ul> <li>Lower <code>threshd_value</code> (try 40, 30, 20...)</li> <li>Check image intensity range \u2014 is it very dim?</li> <li>Verify tuning crop has visible cFos+ cells</li> </ul>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#detecting-too-many-false-positives","title":"\"Detecting too many false positives\"","text":"<ul> <li>Increase <code>threshd_value</code></li> <li>Increase <code>min_wshed_size</code> to filter small debris</li> <li>Adjust <code>tophat_radius</code> if background not removed</li> </ul>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#cells-not-separated-correctly","title":"\"Cells not separated correctly\"","text":"<ul> <li>Increase <code>dog_sigma1</code> or <code>dog_sigma2</code> for better edge detection</li> <li>Check that detected maxima are inside cells</li> </ul>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#registration-looks-wrong","title":"\"Registration looks wrong\"","text":"<ul> <li>Check <code>ref_orientation</code> \u2014 are axes mapped correctly?</li> <li>Verify <code>downsample_rough</code> matches your resolution</li> <li>Use <code>VisualCheck.combine_reg()</code> to diagnose</li> </ul>"},{"location":"tutorials/quickstart.html#next-steps","title":"Next Steps","text":"<ul> <li>Process multiple images \u2014 Batch processing guide</li> <li>Configure parameters \u2014 Detailed parameter reference</li> <li>Visual QC \u2014 Quality control tools</li> <li>Understand the algorithm \u2014 How cell detection works</li> </ul>"}]}